WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.800 align:middle line:90%


00:00:00.800 --> 00:00:02.832 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:02.832 --> 00:00:08.029 align:middle line:90%


00:00:08.029 --> 00:00:09.890 align:middle line:84%
>> Hi, it's James here
from "Food Matters."

00:00:09.890 --> 00:00:13.280 align:middle line:10%
And I'm eminently excited
to bring you a special guest

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:14.250 align:middle line:10%
today.

00:00:14.250 --> 00:00:16.850 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to be chatting
with Ira Israel.

00:00:16.850 --> 00:00:20.600 align:middle line:84%
My wife Laurentine met
Ira at a spiritual center

00:00:20.600 --> 00:00:22.380 align:middle line:84%
in Los Angeles a
number of years ago.

00:00:22.380 --> 00:00:24.890 align:middle line:84%
And since then, we've
crossed paths many times.

00:00:24.890 --> 00:00:27.440 align:middle line:84%
He is a psychotherapist,
counselor,

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:29.840 align:middle line:84%
and mindfulness
relationship expert,

00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:33.740 align:middle line:84%
and he's taught mindfulness
to psychologists,

00:00:33.740 --> 00:00:37.520 align:middle line:84%
medical practitioners,
attorneys, everyday people all

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:38.600 align:middle line:90%
around the world.

00:00:38.600 --> 00:00:40.760 align:middle line:84%
And he's got a
fantastic book called

00:00:40.760 --> 00:00:44.250 align:middle line:84%
"How to Overcome Your Childhood
Now That You're an Adult."

00:00:44.250 --> 00:00:46.160 align:middle line:84%
It's a fantastic read,
and it's something

00:00:46.160 --> 00:00:48.327 align:middle line:84%
that is very important in
this day and age, I think,

00:00:48.327 --> 00:00:50.985 align:middle line:84%
as we start to reflect on how
we've been shaped as a human

00:00:50.985 --> 00:00:53.360 align:middle line:84%
and how we can overcome some
of the trauma and challenges

00:00:53.360 --> 00:00:57.800 align:middle line:84%
that we may have been exposed
to in our younger years.

00:00:57.800 --> 00:00:58.760 align:middle line:90%
Ira.

00:00:58.760 --> 00:01:00.390 align:middle line:84%
>> James, thank you
for having me here.

00:01:00.390 --> 00:01:02.040 align:middle line:90%
>> I'm excited to chat.

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:05.300 align:middle line:84%
So where I normally start
most conversations is really

00:01:05.300 --> 00:01:07.910 align:middle line:90%
around this idea of--

00:01:07.910 --> 00:01:10.490 align:middle line:84%
I find that most people
have some form of catalyst

00:01:10.490 --> 00:01:13.940 align:middle line:84%
or something that happened
to then that sort of put them

00:01:13.940 --> 00:01:16.910 align:middle line:84%
on this trajectory of
being, in your case,

00:01:16.910 --> 00:01:20.060 align:middle line:84%
in the mindfulness sort
of space or industry.

00:01:20.060 --> 00:01:22.130 align:middle line:84%
How did that start
for you, and what

00:01:22.130 --> 00:01:24.230 align:middle line:90%
was this journey like for you?

00:01:24.230 --> 00:01:29.930 align:middle line:84%
>> In January of 1985, I was
a passenger in a car accident,

00:01:29.930 --> 00:01:32.780 align:middle line:84%
and my face was
blown off my head,

00:01:32.780 --> 00:01:36.330 align:middle line:84%
and my femur was
shattered into 200 pieces.

00:01:36.330 --> 00:01:40.790 align:middle line:84%
Normally, some of the bone
pierces the femoral artery

00:01:40.790 --> 00:01:43.250 align:middle line:90%
and you bleed out in 50 seconds.

00:01:43.250 --> 00:01:46.930 align:middle line:84%
And instead, a
doctor was called in.

00:01:46.930 --> 00:01:49.400 align:middle line:84%
He was called in
to amputate my leg.

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:53.280 align:middle line:84%
And he said, I just
read this article.

00:01:53.280 --> 00:01:56.960 align:middle line:84%
A Swiss doctor named Zichal
has this contraption.

00:01:56.960 --> 00:01:58.460 align:middle line:90%
I'm not going to amputate.

00:01:58.460 --> 00:02:01.790 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to put him in traction
and put him back together.

00:02:01.790 --> 00:02:05.880 align:middle line:84%
So over the next
couple of years,

00:02:05.880 --> 00:02:08.840 align:middle line:84%
I started asking, like,
what's the meaning of life,

00:02:08.840 --> 00:02:11.548 align:middle line:84%
and why is the world so messed
up, and all these things.

00:02:11.548 --> 00:02:14.090 align:middle line:84%
And I went on this journey that
I didn't know I was going on.

00:02:14.090 --> 00:02:16.460 align:middle line:84%
It actually took 25 years,
which I'm not proud of.

00:02:16.460 --> 00:02:17.990 align:middle line:90%
I feel like a slow learner.

00:02:17.990 --> 00:02:21.290 align:middle line:84%
But for the first eight
years, I studied philosophy.

00:02:21.290 --> 00:02:27.060 align:middle line:90%
And then in Thailand in '94, I--

00:02:27.060 --> 00:02:29.030 align:middle line:90%
again, this is my idiocy.

00:02:29.030 --> 00:02:31.850 align:middle line:84%
I walked into a door frame
because I'm tall, right?

00:02:31.850 --> 00:02:35.210 align:middle line:84%
And a woman healed
me with her hands.

00:02:35.210 --> 00:02:37.940 align:middle line:84%
And so I started thinking,
like, maybe all this philosophy

00:02:37.940 --> 00:02:39.680 align:middle line:90%
is kind of misguided.

00:02:39.680 --> 00:02:41.000 align:middle line:90%
Maybe there's other things.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:43.040 align:middle line:84%
So then I started
studying spirituality.

00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:45.500 align:middle line:84%
So I studied Buddhism,
Hinduism, Kabbalah.

00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:49.130 align:middle line:84%
And then, eight years
later, I started studying--

00:02:49.130 --> 00:02:50.400 align:middle line:90%
I was in a relationship.

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:53.000 align:middle line:90%
It was not going swimmingly.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:54.890 align:middle line:84%
And so I started
studying psychology.

00:02:54.890 --> 00:02:59.150 align:middle line:84%
So over those 25 years-- and
I had gone to film school,

00:02:59.150 --> 00:03:01.670 align:middle line:84%
and I had gone to
yoga teacher training.

00:03:01.670 --> 00:03:02.975 align:middle line:90%
I got into meditation.

00:03:02.975 --> 00:03:04.850 align:middle line:84%
And then all of a sudden,
I was teaching yoga

00:03:04.850 --> 00:03:09.620 align:middle line:84%
at Rodney Yee's yoga studio
and a woman walked in

00:03:09.620 --> 00:03:10.970 align:middle line:90%
and she put her hands down.

00:03:10.970 --> 00:03:13.970 align:middle line:84%
And I don't know how insane this
sounds, but I heard a voice.

00:03:13.970 --> 00:03:18.140 align:middle line:84%
And it said, OK,
it's time to teach.

00:03:18.140 --> 00:03:20.480 align:middle line:84%
Like, you've been
indulgent for 25 years.

00:03:20.480 --> 00:03:22.610 align:middle line:84%
You've been just
studying all this stuff.

00:03:22.610 --> 00:03:24.740 align:middle line:90%
Now it's time to give back.

00:03:24.740 --> 00:03:28.280 align:middle line:84%
And it's really interesting,
because during those 25 years,

00:03:28.280 --> 00:03:30.050 align:middle line:84%
if you looked at my
life from the outside,

00:03:30.050 --> 00:03:32.870 align:middle line:84%
you'd be like, oh
yea, the poor soul.

00:03:32.870 --> 00:03:36.930 align:middle line:84%
He's in an ashram in India
or he's in a cafe in Paris

00:03:36.930 --> 00:03:40.160 align:middle line:84%
or-- like, you know, it wasn't
a terrible life, but it was--

00:03:40.160 --> 00:03:44.900 align:middle line:84%
there was no, like, central
focus other than, like, Ira

00:03:44.900 --> 00:03:47.360 align:middle line:84%
indulgently
questioning everything.

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:51.560 align:middle line:84%
And then, right from
that point in time,

00:03:51.560 --> 00:03:53.480 align:middle line:90%
I put an ad on Craigslist.

00:03:53.480 --> 00:03:56.870 align:middle line:84%
I hired a cinematographer
and a director

00:03:56.870 --> 00:03:59.330 align:middle line:84%
and I made "Yoga for
Depression and Anxiety."

00:03:59.330 --> 00:04:01.370 align:middle line:84%
It became a bestseller
three months later,

00:04:01.370 --> 00:04:03.245 align:middle line:84%
and then I made "Mindfulness
for Depression."

00:04:03.245 --> 00:04:04.640 align:middle line:84%
I made "Mindfulness
for Anxiety."

00:04:04.640 --> 00:04:08.780 align:middle line:84%
And then it everything collapsed
into this, like, perfect--

00:04:08.780 --> 00:04:10.520 align:middle line:84%
this is who you're
supposed to be.

00:04:10.520 --> 00:04:12.410 align:middle line:84%
So it's fascinating
to me because I see--

00:04:12.410 --> 00:04:16.490 align:middle line:84%
when I have patients in my
office now, when they come in,

00:04:16.490 --> 00:04:19.100 align:middle line:90%
I can kind of get a feel--

00:04:19.100 --> 00:04:21.260 align:middle line:84%
like, oh yeah,
that was me when I

00:04:21.260 --> 00:04:24.330 align:middle line:84%
was at the beginning or the
middle or kind of the end.

00:04:24.330 --> 00:04:25.980 align:middle line:84%
And something will
come together.

00:04:25.980 --> 00:04:27.740 align:middle line:84%
We don't know what it
is, but the universe

00:04:27.740 --> 00:04:29.198 align:middle line:84%
will give you
information, and then

00:04:29.198 --> 00:04:31.450 align:middle line:84%
you'll become who
you're supposed to be.

00:04:31.450 --> 00:04:36.510 align:middle line:84%
It's really interesting
because I study

00:04:36.510 --> 00:04:38.690 align:middle line:90%
how your mind represses things.

00:04:38.690 --> 00:04:42.350 align:middle line:84%
And then they come up
at different times.

00:04:42.350 --> 00:04:44.870 align:middle line:84%
But the repressions--
you know, what

00:04:44.870 --> 00:04:47.240 align:middle line:84%
Freud said about repressions--
whatever's repressed

00:04:47.240 --> 00:04:49.760 align:middle line:90%
comes back thricefold.

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:54.650 align:middle line:84%
So I've worked hard in therapy
and with plant medicine

00:04:54.650 --> 00:04:57.440 align:middle line:84%
and with shamans and
healers and things

00:04:57.440 --> 00:05:06.380 align:middle line:84%
so that I've integrated
the pain, because somebody

00:05:06.380 --> 00:05:07.238 align:middle line:90%
told me--

00:05:07.238 --> 00:05:09.530 align:middle line:84%
you remember certain things
from being in the hospital.

00:05:09.530 --> 00:05:13.940 align:middle line:84%
Someone told me that the most
painful thing a woman can

00:05:13.940 --> 00:05:15.830 align:middle line:84%
experience is
natural childbirth,

00:05:15.830 --> 00:05:19.010 align:middle line:84%
and the most painful
experience a man can experience

00:05:19.010 --> 00:05:22.670 align:middle line:90%
is a femur broken.

00:05:22.670 --> 00:05:27.980 align:middle line:84%
It takes a piano from
five stories dropped down.

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:30.000 align:middle line:84%
Your femur's the largest
bone in your body.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:31.100 align:middle line:90%
It's the strongest thing.

00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:33.090 align:middle line:84%
And so the top of
mine was just--

00:05:33.090 --> 00:05:35.870 align:middle line:90%
it was just fragments, pieces.

00:05:35.870 --> 00:05:40.190 align:middle line:84%
And I obviously was
in a lot of pain.

00:05:40.190 --> 00:05:43.050 align:middle line:90%
But there was, you know--

00:05:43.050 --> 00:05:46.490 align:middle line:84%
and I'll tell you an
interesting story.

00:05:46.490 --> 00:05:49.380 align:middle line:84%
15 years later, I was
in a yoga class, right?

00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:53.600 align:middle line:90%
And I went to this gentleman.

00:05:53.600 --> 00:05:55.250 align:middle line:90%
I'm not going to name his name.

00:05:55.250 --> 00:05:58.410 align:middle line:84%
But people will know who he
is when I tell the story.

00:05:58.410 --> 00:06:01.627 align:middle line:84%
So I had moved to Santa Barbara
to study Buddhism and Hinduism.

00:06:01.627 --> 00:06:03.710 align:middle line:84%
And people said, you got
to do yoga with this guy.

00:06:03.710 --> 00:06:05.210 align:middle line:90%
You gotta do yoga with this guy.

00:06:05.210 --> 00:06:09.890 align:middle line:84%
So I go to this class,
and I'm a hardcore purist

00:06:09.890 --> 00:06:11.040 align:middle line:90%
about everything.

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:14.210 align:middle line:84%
And so after about 20 minutes,
the guy shuts off the lights

00:06:14.210 --> 00:06:16.120 align:middle line:84%
and he plays "I Will
Survive," and he

00:06:16.120 --> 00:06:18.120 align:middle line:90%
says, "Dance on your mat."

00:06:18.120 --> 00:06:23.090 align:middle line:84%
And I was not open to
that, and I just, like--

00:06:23.090 --> 00:06:24.428 align:middle line:90%
I rolled up my mat and left.

00:06:24.428 --> 00:06:25.970 align:middle line:84%
I was like, that
guy's a weirdo, man.

00:06:25.970 --> 00:06:27.830 align:middle line:84%
I'm not into that
California bullshit.

00:06:27.830 --> 00:06:29.330 align:middle line:90%
Like, I want to do yoga, man.

00:06:29.330 --> 00:06:31.290 align:middle line:84%
You know, I was
just, like, crazy.

00:06:31.290 --> 00:06:35.183 align:middle line:84%
So like a year and
a half later, I

00:06:35.183 --> 00:06:37.350 align:middle line:84%
was like, OK, people are
saying, you got to go back.

00:06:37.350 --> 00:06:38.240 align:middle line:90%
He doesn't do that all time.

00:06:38.240 --> 00:06:38.830 align:middle line:90%
You got to go back.

00:06:38.830 --> 00:06:39.170 align:middle line:90%
You got to go back.

00:06:39.170 --> 00:06:40.280 align:middle line:90%
And I went back.

00:06:40.280 --> 00:06:44.990 align:middle line:84%
And he remembered
me from walking out.

00:06:44.990 --> 00:06:47.040 align:middle line:84%
And he had asked at
the beginning of class,

00:06:47.040 --> 00:06:48.290 align:middle line:90%
does anyone have any injuries?

00:06:48.290 --> 00:06:51.780 align:middle line:84%
And I told him about my
injuries and whatnot.

00:06:51.780 --> 00:06:55.460 align:middle line:90%
So it's two years later, right?

00:06:55.460 --> 00:06:57.620 align:middle line:84%
I'm in Pigeon Pose
on the left side.

00:06:57.620 --> 00:07:01.130 align:middle line:84%
The guy hasn't touched
me all class, right?

00:07:01.130 --> 00:07:03.320 align:middle line:90%
He's my size, 200 pounds.

00:07:03.320 --> 00:07:04.850 align:middle line:90%
He comes over.

00:07:04.850 --> 00:07:06.530 align:middle line:84%
My leg's in front
of me like this.

00:07:06.530 --> 00:07:14.960 align:middle line:84%
He puts his weight on my back,
and he whispers in my ear,

00:07:14.960 --> 00:07:18.970 align:middle line:84%
"I remember that you have an
issue with your left leg."

00:07:18.970 --> 00:07:24.585 align:middle line:84%
And I snapped back into the car
screaming, "Don't let me die.

00:07:24.585 --> 00:07:25.460 align:middle line:90%
I don't want to die."

00:07:25.460 --> 00:07:29.880 align:middle line:90%


00:07:29.880 --> 00:07:32.330 align:middle line:90%
And so your mind--

00:07:32.330 --> 00:07:35.270 align:middle line:84%
I was saying that to
a paramedic, you know?

00:07:35.270 --> 00:07:39.560 align:middle line:84%
And that's, like,
the glimpse I have

00:07:39.560 --> 00:07:45.307 align:middle line:84%
of the week that's been
repressed where someone drilled

00:07:45.307 --> 00:07:46.890 align:middle line:84%
a hole through my
leg and other people

00:07:46.890 --> 00:07:49.670 align:middle line:84%
were putting things in here and
putting my face back together

00:07:49.670 --> 00:07:51.110 align:middle line:90%
and doing all this stuff.

00:07:51.110 --> 00:07:57.710 align:middle line:84%
But, you know,
it's not a contest.

00:07:57.710 --> 00:08:01.040 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it's stupid
for me to say I

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:03.460 align:middle line:90%
experienced this terrible pain.

00:08:03.460 --> 00:08:10.850 align:middle line:84%
I'm with patients every day,
and I cry about their traumas

00:08:10.850 --> 00:08:12.200 align:middle line:90%
more than I--

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:14.000 align:middle line:84%
or as much as I cry
about my traumas.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:15.820 align:middle line:90%
This is life, you know?

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:18.440 align:middle line:90%
We want to be loved.

00:08:18.440 --> 00:08:22.020 align:middle line:90%
We don't have good tools.

00:08:22.020 --> 00:08:26.060 align:middle line:84%
Things happen, and
it's very traumatizing.

00:08:26.060 --> 00:08:31.820 align:middle line:84%
And the best we can do is
nurture our own resilience so

00:08:31.820 --> 00:08:36.320 align:middle line:84%
that we can show up and
have some understanding

00:08:36.320 --> 00:08:40.770 align:middle line:84%
and create a narrative and
transmute our own suffering

00:08:40.770 --> 00:08:45.980 align:middle line:84%
into making the
world a better place

00:08:45.980 --> 00:08:49.370 align:middle line:84%
by not doing the
natural thing of paying

00:08:49.370 --> 00:08:53.090 align:middle line:84%
our suffering forward, by
showing up in a way and saying,

00:08:53.090 --> 00:08:56.390 align:middle line:84%
no, my mind is telling me
to go and hurt that person.

00:08:56.390 --> 00:08:59.310 align:middle line:84%
And instead, I'm
going to forgive them.

00:08:59.310 --> 00:09:02.770 align:middle line:84%
I want that person
to have a great life.

00:09:02.770 --> 00:09:04.520 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, that's awesome.

00:09:04.520 --> 00:09:08.060 align:middle line:84%
Can we stay a little bit on
the story of this car crash,

00:09:08.060 --> 00:09:10.160 align:middle line:84%
because it seems like a
big sort of point for you

00:09:10.160 --> 00:09:11.660 align:middle line:90%
in your journey.

00:09:11.660 --> 00:09:15.820 align:middle line:90%
After that crash happened--

00:09:15.820 --> 00:09:17.660 align:middle line:90%
so you had this leg issue.

00:09:17.660 --> 00:09:20.990 align:middle line:84%
You also talk about the face,
and it went through, and then

00:09:20.990 --> 00:09:22.610 align:middle line:84%
what are some of the
emotions that you

00:09:22.610 --> 00:09:25.370 align:middle line:84%
went through sort of in
the first immediate years

00:09:25.370 --> 00:09:26.810 align:middle line:90%
after that?

00:09:26.810 --> 00:09:37.380 align:middle line:84%
>> The thing that was most
transformational was that--

00:09:37.380 --> 00:09:43.690 align:middle line:84%
so I would go out for years
after, and people would say,

00:09:43.690 --> 00:09:45.440 align:middle line:84%
hey, how'd you get
that scar on your face?

00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:49.020 align:middle line:84%
Or it'd be like I'd be out
at some place or I even--

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:49.820 align:middle line:90%
I'll never forget.

00:09:49.820 --> 00:09:51.530 align:middle line:84%
Some woman came up
to me in a bar once.

00:09:51.530 --> 00:09:53.690 align:middle line:84%
She said, what happened
to your face, you know?

00:09:53.690 --> 00:09:55.632 align:middle line:84%
And people-- and I
meet them all time,

00:09:55.632 --> 00:09:56.840 align:middle line:90%
people who have facial scars.

00:09:56.840 --> 00:09:59.610 align:middle line:84%
It's very traumatizing
because that's

00:09:59.610 --> 00:10:01.837 align:middle line:90%
your facade to the world.

00:10:01.837 --> 00:10:03.170 align:middle line:90%
You're like this is your person.

00:10:03.170 --> 00:10:07.040 align:middle line:84%
And mine was-- it took
five different surgeries

00:10:07.040 --> 00:10:10.460 align:middle line:84%
to put it back together so that
I have some kind of semblance

00:10:10.460 --> 00:10:11.515 align:middle line:90%
of a normal smile.

00:10:11.515 --> 00:10:16.140 align:middle line:84%
I'm very fortunate to have
not had my teeth blown out.

00:10:16.140 --> 00:10:21.080 align:middle line:84%
So I always would
say, kind of proudly,

00:10:21.080 --> 00:10:22.790 align:middle line:84%
I was almost killed
in a car accident.

00:10:22.790 --> 00:10:26.360 align:middle line:84%
So for about 25
years until I started

00:10:26.360 --> 00:10:29.330 align:middle line:84%
getting more and more into
compassion and Buddhism

00:10:29.330 --> 00:10:30.570 align:middle line:90%
and things like that--

00:10:30.570 --> 00:10:33.798 align:middle line:84%
and finally, I took
a course, and you had

00:10:33.798 --> 00:10:35.090 align:middle line:90%
to tell the story of your life.

00:10:35.090 --> 00:10:39.967 align:middle line:84%
And someone said, OK,
what happened here?

00:10:39.967 --> 00:10:42.050 align:middle line:84%
And I said, I was almost
killed in a car accident.

00:10:42.050 --> 00:10:46.580 align:middle line:84%
And there was a
gentleman who was tasked

00:10:46.580 --> 00:10:49.190 align:middle line:90%
with deconstructing the story.

00:10:49.190 --> 00:10:51.430 align:middle line:84%
And so I said, I was almost
killed in a car accident.

00:10:51.430 --> 00:10:53.105 align:middle line:90%
He goes, no, you weren't.

00:10:53.105 --> 00:10:55.230 align:middle line:84%
And I said, well, actually,
my femur was shattered.

00:10:55.230 --> 00:10:56.480 align:middle line:90%
My face was blown off my head.

00:10:56.480 --> 00:10:58.760 align:middle line:84%
They didn't notify my
parents because they didn't

00:10:58.760 --> 00:10:59.990 align:middle line:90%
think I was going to live.

00:10:59.990 --> 00:11:02.120 align:middle line:84%
Trust me, I was almost
killed in a car accident.

00:11:02.120 --> 00:11:03.950 align:middle line:90%
He goes, no, you weren't.

00:11:03.950 --> 00:11:05.070 align:middle line:90%
We went back and forth.

00:11:05.070 --> 00:11:08.300 align:middle line:84%
And then, finally, he says,
there was a car accident.

00:11:08.300 --> 00:11:09.560 align:middle line:90%
Everything else you added.

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:12.230 align:middle line:90%


00:11:12.230 --> 00:11:13.710 align:middle line:90%
You can't be almost pregnant.

00:11:13.710 --> 00:11:15.380 align:middle line:90%
You can't be almost dead.

00:11:15.380 --> 00:11:16.880 align:middle line:90%
You're either alive or dead.

00:11:16.880 --> 00:11:17.960 align:middle line:90%
There was a car accident.

00:11:17.960 --> 00:11:20.090 align:middle line:90%
So language creates reality.

00:11:20.090 --> 00:11:23.090 align:middle line:84%
The way you choose
to frame your life--

00:11:23.090 --> 00:11:26.240 align:middle line:84%
and you're either the
hero of your story

00:11:26.240 --> 00:11:27.140 align:middle line:90%
or you're the victim.

00:11:27.140 --> 00:11:30.500 align:middle line:84%
And for those first 25 years,
I realized in that instant

00:11:30.500 --> 00:11:33.140 align:middle line:84%
that I was sucking
people into my drama,

00:11:33.140 --> 00:11:35.840 align:middle line:84%
trying to get them
to be empathetic,

00:11:35.840 --> 00:11:39.350 align:middle line:84%
and I just made a
conscious choice, like, no.

00:11:39.350 --> 00:11:43.460 align:middle line:84%
So when people ask me now, it's
like, there was a car accident.

00:11:43.460 --> 00:11:44.570 align:middle line:90%
Language creates reality.

00:11:44.570 --> 00:11:49.490 align:middle line:84%
I mean, really we have to
be impeccable in the words

00:11:49.490 --> 00:11:56.760 align:middle line:84%
that we choose
because we're trying

00:11:56.760 --> 00:12:00.210 align:middle line:84%
to cultivate authentic
love, and you can't do

00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:05.400 align:middle line:90%
that if you're just a facade.

00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:08.430 align:middle line:84%
>> That was probably one of the
most profound parts of the book

00:12:08.430 --> 00:12:12.133 align:middle line:84%
of yours that I read,
this realization that you

00:12:12.133 --> 00:12:13.050 align:middle line:90%
weren't almost killed.

00:12:13.050 --> 00:12:15.000 align:middle line:84%
Like, you can't almost
be pregnant, right?

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:16.260 align:middle line:90%
You can't almost be killed.

00:12:16.260 --> 00:12:17.870 align:middle line:90%
You're either alive or dead.

00:12:17.870 --> 00:12:21.565 align:middle line:84%
It's like, I was in a car
accident or even positive--

00:12:21.565 --> 00:12:23.190 align:middle line:84%
I survived a car
accident would be even

00:12:23.190 --> 00:12:24.910 align:middle line:90%
more of a positive spin on it.

00:12:24.910 --> 00:12:25.710 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:12:25.710 --> 00:12:27.520 align:middle line:84%
>> And there was
also this part--

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:28.770 align:middle line:90%
I don't mean to labor on this.

00:12:28.770 --> 00:12:30.540 align:middle line:90%
We'll get to more things.

00:12:30.540 --> 00:12:33.930 align:middle line:84%
But you actually looked up the
gentleman that was with you.

00:12:33.930 --> 00:12:35.928 align:middle line:84%
So this was in
your teens, right?

00:12:35.928 --> 00:12:37.470 align:middle line:84%
So if you could
mention that as well.

00:12:37.470 --> 00:12:40.290 align:middle line:84%
So you were 18 at the
time or something, or 19.

00:12:40.290 --> 00:12:44.670 align:middle line:84%
And so at that age, I mean, I've
been in cars with 18-year-olds.

00:12:44.670 --> 00:12:45.858 align:middle line:90%
People drive like losers.

00:12:45.858 --> 00:12:47.400 align:middle line:84%
You know, you've
got your feet pushed

00:12:47.400 --> 00:12:50.025 align:middle line:84%
through the bottom of the floor
because you're like, slow down,

00:12:50.025 --> 00:12:51.900 align:middle line:90%
slow down, buddy, you know?

00:12:51.900 --> 00:12:55.080 align:middle line:84%
And so to go back and apologize
to someone, first of all,

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:56.100 align:middle line:90%
or to find them--

00:12:56.100 --> 00:12:59.400 align:middle line:84%
you know, difficult. But
then to muster up the courage

00:12:59.400 --> 00:13:01.350 align:middle line:84%
to do that and to
do it authentically

00:13:01.350 --> 00:13:03.195 align:middle line:84%
and to really make
peace with that is huge.

00:13:03.195 --> 00:13:04.070 align:middle line:90%
Tell me that process.

00:13:04.070 --> 00:13:05.040 align:middle line:90%
So how old were you?

00:13:05.040 --> 00:13:06.457 align:middle line:84%
Like, what went
through your mind?

00:13:06.457 --> 00:13:08.550 align:middle line:84%
And then how much later
was it when you finally

00:13:08.550 --> 00:13:09.870 align:middle line:90%
reconciled this?

00:13:09.870 --> 00:13:13.950 align:middle line:84%
>> So I had been
studying compassion,

00:13:13.950 --> 00:13:18.090 align:middle line:84%
and the term that I use
in the book is at onement

00:13:18.090 --> 00:13:22.110 align:middle line:84%
or atonement, and the
key tool is forgiveness.

00:13:22.110 --> 00:13:27.600 align:middle line:84%
So I took a compassion
workshop, and it was fascinating

00:13:27.600 --> 00:13:29.400 align:middle line:90%
because I had been having--

00:13:29.400 --> 00:13:31.610 align:middle line:90%
I'll be frank here.

00:13:31.610 --> 00:13:34.050 align:middle line:84%
If during the first 25 years
after the car accident--

00:13:34.050 --> 00:13:36.930 align:middle line:90%
this is so embarrassing--

00:13:36.930 --> 00:13:40.110 align:middle line:84%
if someone had said, I'm sorry,
you have pancreatic cancer,

00:13:40.110 --> 00:13:42.480 align:middle line:84%
you're going to
die in two months--

00:13:42.480 --> 00:13:49.620 align:middle line:84%
I had this vengeance fantasy
of going to find this driver

00:13:49.620 --> 00:13:52.890 align:middle line:84%
and doing to his face
what happened to mine.

00:13:52.890 --> 00:13:55.500 align:middle line:84%
And I would find myself,
like, in the middle

00:13:55.500 --> 00:13:58.650 align:middle line:84%
of the night sometimes just
having these horrible--

00:13:58.650 --> 00:14:00.450 align:middle line:84%
you know, like, the
world isn't just

00:14:00.450 --> 00:14:03.090 align:middle line:90%
and this whole terrible thing.

00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:06.840 align:middle line:84%
And there was something
that Fred Luskin, who

00:14:06.840 --> 00:14:08.250 align:middle line:84%
wrote "Forgive
for Good--" he was

00:14:08.250 --> 00:14:11.117 align:middle line:90%
speaking about these topics.

00:14:11.117 --> 00:14:13.200 align:middle line:84%
And so I went home from
the conference that night,

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:20.100 align:middle line:84%
and I wrote a letter to the
guy, the driver of the car.

00:14:20.100 --> 00:14:22.530 align:middle line:90%
And I just put it away.

00:14:22.530 --> 00:14:24.150 align:middle line:84%
I didn't mean to
send it or anything.

00:14:24.150 --> 00:14:26.810 align:middle line:84%
And then I woke up the next
morning, and I read it,

00:14:26.810 --> 00:14:29.012 align:middle line:84%
and I was just like,
let me check out

00:14:29.012 --> 00:14:29.970 align:middle line:90%
what's on the internet.

00:14:29.970 --> 00:14:34.140 align:middle line:84%
So I googled him,
found him on Facebook,

00:14:34.140 --> 00:14:37.590 align:middle line:84%
and I set up a second
Ira Israel account

00:14:37.590 --> 00:14:39.240 align:middle line:84%
so he would see
it's me, but I just

00:14:39.240 --> 00:14:41.670 align:middle line:84%
didn't want him to see my
whole life or anything.

00:14:41.670 --> 00:14:46.560 align:middle line:90%
And I sent the letter.

00:14:46.560 --> 00:14:50.500 align:middle line:84%
I just told them what I'd done
for those 25 years and things

00:14:50.500 --> 00:14:53.640 align:middle line:84%
that I was feeling and
whatnot, and I went to work.

00:14:53.640 --> 00:14:56.570 align:middle line:90%
And I came home.

00:14:56.570 --> 00:14:58.940 align:middle line:84%
It was probably, like,
6 o'clock at night.

00:14:58.940 --> 00:15:02.550 align:middle line:84%
And I was like, OK, let me check
this other Facebook account.

00:15:02.550 --> 00:15:08.190 align:middle line:84%
And lo and behold, I received
an equally long letter.

00:15:08.190 --> 00:15:11.350 align:middle line:84%
It was very-- and I
started to read it,

00:15:11.350 --> 00:15:20.370 align:middle line:84%
and it was really heartfelt.
And it's surprising to everybody

00:15:20.370 --> 00:15:22.230 align:middle line:84%
when you show up
in a certain way.

00:15:22.230 --> 00:15:25.470 align:middle line:84%
Like, I can't tell you,
James, be vulnerable, right?

00:15:25.470 --> 00:15:28.110 align:middle line:84%
But if I show up
in a certain way,

00:15:28.110 --> 00:15:31.170 align:middle line:90%
I can inspire you or enroll you.

00:15:31.170 --> 00:15:34.830 align:middle line:84%
So I don't know how much
personal work this person

00:15:34.830 --> 00:15:37.080 align:middle line:84%
had done over the past
25 years or something.

00:15:37.080 --> 00:15:41.460 align:middle line:84%
But he showed up
like a gentleman.

00:15:41.460 --> 00:15:47.350 align:middle line:84%
And we went back and forth for
a week talking about our lives.

00:15:47.350 --> 00:16:01.050 align:middle line:84%
And at the end of the week, he
had told me how sorry he was.

00:16:01.050 --> 00:16:06.070 align:middle line:84%
And for some reason I
just felt compelled,

00:16:06.070 --> 00:16:07.980 align:middle line:84%
and I just wrote
in all capitals,

00:16:07.980 --> 00:16:12.610 align:middle line:84%
"If it helps you in any
way, I forgive you."

00:16:12.610 --> 00:16:20.310 align:middle line:84%
And I closed the account,
and I deleted the account,

00:16:20.310 --> 00:16:27.600 align:middle line:84%
and I never had any of those
machinations or anything.

00:16:27.600 --> 00:16:30.330 align:middle line:84%
Like, all-- like, it's just--
it was the wildest thing.

00:16:30.330 --> 00:16:32.100 align:middle line:84%
It's just, like, all
of the negativity.

00:16:32.100 --> 00:16:32.900 align:middle line:90%
You know?

00:16:32.900 --> 00:16:36.680 align:middle line:84%
And that's why in the book
I talk about this irony--

00:16:36.680 --> 00:16:39.780 align:middle line:84%
because your mind was built to
create resentments-- woulda,

00:16:39.780 --> 00:16:41.250 align:middle line:90%
coulda, shoulda, didn'ts.

00:16:41.250 --> 00:16:45.870 align:middle line:84%
And those are the
things that show up

00:16:45.870 --> 00:16:50.070 align:middle line:84%
as the causes of suffering,
because you're trying

00:16:50.070 --> 00:16:51.480 align:middle line:90%
to change the unchangeable.

00:16:51.480 --> 00:16:57.300 align:middle line:84%
I can't go back to
1985, and if I did,

00:16:57.300 --> 00:16:59.460 align:middle line:84%
something worse might
have happened, right?

00:16:59.460 --> 00:17:04.500 align:middle line:84%
But your mind is this incredible
machine that looks at the past

00:17:04.500 --> 00:17:06.420 align:middle line:84%
and says, wow, that
was really traumatic.

00:17:06.420 --> 00:17:08.460 align:middle line:84%
I'm never going to
let that happen again.

00:17:08.460 --> 00:17:12.359 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to lift weights or
I'm going to be this person

00:17:12.359 --> 00:17:14.160 align:middle line:84%
or I'm going to get
rich or I'll show them

00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:16.260 align:middle line:84%
and you do this
whole crazy thing.

00:17:16.260 --> 00:17:19.980 align:middle line:84%
And you-- I wanted to write
a book about authenticity

00:17:19.980 --> 00:17:23.849 align:middle line:84%
because I felt
that we become what

00:17:23.849 --> 00:17:28.349 align:middle line:84%
we love and we become what we
hate and both are inauthentic.

00:17:28.349 --> 00:17:30.600 align:middle line:84%
So there's a part
of us that wants

00:17:30.600 --> 00:17:33.700 align:middle line:84%
to be loved by our parents
and the people around us.

00:17:33.700 --> 00:17:35.100 align:middle line:90%
So we emulate.

00:17:35.100 --> 00:17:39.170 align:middle line:90%
We imitate them.

00:17:39.170 --> 00:17:41.040 align:middle line:84%
If they're, you know--
and then there's

00:17:41.040 --> 00:17:43.890 align:middle line:84%
this part that is trying
to individuate and become

00:17:43.890 --> 00:17:45.270 align:middle line:90%
our own selves.

00:17:45.270 --> 00:17:48.410 align:middle line:84%
So we get tattoos,
and we have long hair,

00:17:48.410 --> 00:17:51.270 align:middle line:84%
or we buy-- if they
have a German car,

00:17:51.270 --> 00:17:52.980 align:middle line:84%
we buy an American
car, you know?

00:17:52.980 --> 00:17:56.040 align:middle line:84%
And so there's this conflict,
I feel, in all of us

00:17:56.040 --> 00:17:59.730 align:middle line:84%
that we want to be loved,
but we want to be our own--

00:17:59.730 --> 00:18:02.430 align:middle line:90%
we want to have our own agency.

00:18:02.430 --> 00:18:06.730 align:middle line:84%
And forgiveness is
a huge part of that.

00:18:06.730 --> 00:18:08.580 align:middle line:84%
There's a beautiful
quote by Lily Tomlin

00:18:08.580 --> 00:18:09.690 align:middle line:90%
that I quote in the book.

00:18:09.690 --> 00:18:14.370 align:middle line:84%
"Forgiveness means giving up all
hope of having a better past."

00:18:14.370 --> 00:18:16.170 align:middle line:84%
So your mind does
this incredible thing

00:18:16.170 --> 00:18:20.340 align:middle line:84%
where it's constantly trying
to, like, rewrite your history.

00:18:20.340 --> 00:18:27.600 align:middle line:84%
And you're only causing
your own suffering

00:18:27.600 --> 00:18:31.230 align:middle line:84%
because it's like trying to jam
a square peg into a round hole.

00:18:31.230 --> 00:18:33.370 align:middle line:90%
You can't change the past.

00:18:33.370 --> 00:18:36.180 align:middle line:84%
And yet, if you're out
there and you're like, well,

00:18:36.180 --> 00:18:39.000 align:middle line:84%
I'll show them that they
shouldn't have mistreated me

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:42.540 align:middle line:84%
because I'll be famous and
I'll be rich and I'll do these

00:18:42.540 --> 00:18:46.020 align:middle line:84%
things, you'll get there and
then you'll realize that those

00:18:46.020 --> 00:18:47.300 align:middle line:90%
people don't--

00:18:47.300 --> 00:18:48.300 align:middle line:90%
you don't exist to them.

00:18:48.300 --> 00:18:53.910 align:middle line:84%
So you've lived your whole life
for this inauthentic reason,

00:18:53.910 --> 00:18:57.660 align:middle line:84%
like, this vengeance fairy tale
or this, like, I'll show them.

00:18:57.660 --> 00:19:02.280 align:middle line:84%
So I really hope that, in
my classes and in the book

00:19:02.280 --> 00:19:05.790 align:middle line:84%
and on the DVDs, that
I inspire people just

00:19:05.790 --> 00:19:11.220 align:middle line:84%
to question their whys,
why they're doing things,

00:19:11.220 --> 00:19:16.260 align:middle line:84%
and then realize that
there is a set of tools

00:19:16.260 --> 00:19:21.030 align:middle line:84%
available to keep us at the high
end of our happiness spectrums.

00:19:21.030 --> 00:19:23.280 align:middle line:84%
The only thing that correlates
strongly with happiness

00:19:23.280 --> 00:19:25.155 align:middle line:84%
is the quality of our
intimate relationships,

00:19:25.155 --> 00:19:28.003 align:middle line:84%
how we connect
with other people.

00:19:28.003 --> 00:19:32.280 align:middle line:84%
Money-- nobody wants worked
really hard on their tombstone.

00:19:32.280 --> 00:19:34.330 align:middle line:84%
And yet, if we go across
the street right now,

00:19:34.330 --> 00:19:36.210 align:middle line:84%
there'll be kids in
cafes with earbuds

00:19:36.210 --> 00:19:39.640 align:middle line:84%
on just thinking that
they're working really hard--

00:19:39.640 --> 00:19:44.940 align:middle line:84%
and so this whole American
fiction of, like, homeownership

00:19:44.940 --> 00:19:47.070 align:middle line:84%
and going into debt
and all these things

00:19:47.070 --> 00:19:50.560 align:middle line:84%
that keep people amped up
and in fight or flight mode

00:19:50.560 --> 00:19:55.650 align:middle line:84%
and not sleeping well and then
eventually cancer or depression

00:19:55.650 --> 00:19:57.120 align:middle line:90%
or these things.

00:19:57.120 --> 00:19:59.880 align:middle line:84%
We really have to just
sit down and question

00:19:59.880 --> 00:20:02.910 align:middle line:84%
all the underlying
systems in our culture

00:20:02.910 --> 00:20:05.670 align:middle line:84%
and see which ones are
bringing out the best in us

00:20:05.670 --> 00:20:10.050 align:middle line:84%
and making us compassionate,
loving, authentic human beings.

00:20:10.050 --> 00:20:10.920 align:middle line:90%
>> I agree.

00:20:10.920 --> 00:20:14.730 align:middle line:90%
It's a big system to unravel.

00:20:14.730 --> 00:20:16.800 align:middle line:84%
Before we jump to
this depression

00:20:16.800 --> 00:20:20.020 align:middle line:84%
and our modern landscape of
everything that we've created,

00:20:20.020 --> 00:20:21.900 align:middle line:84%
which I really want
to get to, I want

00:20:21.900 --> 00:20:24.930 align:middle line:84%
to stay for a little bit
on this topic of sort

00:20:24.930 --> 00:20:30.730 align:middle line:84%
of the primary caregivers and
how they can impact your life.

00:20:30.730 --> 00:20:34.170 align:middle line:84%
So you talk about how when we're
young, we do a lot of things

00:20:34.170 --> 00:20:36.120 align:middle line:90%
to get love and approval.

00:20:36.120 --> 00:20:39.000 align:middle line:84%
And then when we're
older, we sort of wonder

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:41.377 align:middle line:84%
why we're doing things or
what's the best thing we should

00:20:41.377 --> 00:20:42.960 align:middle line:84%
do in our life, and
we're questioning,

00:20:42.960 --> 00:20:44.040 align:middle line:90%
how can we be authentic?

