because it has no self.

00:21:25.140 --> 00:21:30.210 align:middle line:84%
So we are creatures of language,
and there's this individuation

00:21:30.210 --> 00:21:34.140 align:middle line:84%
process where a baby
finally is like,

00:21:34.140 --> 00:21:36.600 align:middle line:84%
you know, looking at
the mirror and then

00:21:36.600 --> 00:21:39.300 align:middle line:84%
finally looking at the mother
and realizing that it's not

00:21:39.300 --> 00:21:40.770 align:middle line:90%
at one with the mother.

00:21:40.770 --> 00:21:45.180 align:middle line:84%
And we individuate in
America very abruptly.

00:21:45.180 --> 00:21:48.630 align:middle line:84%
Science says-- medicine
says that breastfeeding

00:21:48.630 --> 00:21:50.430 align:middle line:90%
for 18 months is optimum.

00:21:50.430 --> 00:21:52.450 align:middle line:90%
I was born in 1966.

00:21:52.450 --> 00:21:54.820 align:middle line:84%
And the doctors went
to my parents and said,

00:21:54.820 --> 00:21:56.520 align:middle line:84%
we have this chemical
formula that's

00:21:56.520 --> 00:21:57.980 align:middle line:90%
superior to mother's milk.

00:21:57.980 --> 00:21:59.820 align:middle line:84%
So there's a whole
swath of people

00:21:59.820 --> 00:22:01.380 align:middle line:90%
who were never breastfed.

00:22:01.380 --> 00:22:06.090 align:middle line:84%
And I think that correlates to
our poor attachment dynamics

00:22:06.090 --> 00:22:09.570 align:middle line:84%
later in life because we're
interdependent beings.

00:22:09.570 --> 00:22:14.940 align:middle line:84%
And if you are put down as
a baby and allowed to-- you

00:22:14.940 --> 00:22:18.060 align:middle line:84%
know, they allow babies to
cry themselves out, right?

00:22:18.060 --> 00:22:23.730 align:middle line:84%
And it's essentially
the baby assimilates

00:22:23.730 --> 00:22:25.920 align:middle line:90%
that as you're killing me.

00:22:25.920 --> 00:22:27.152 align:middle line:90%
Like, I can't survive alone.

00:22:27.152 --> 00:22:29.610 align:middle line:84%
And you're like, don't worry,
we'll be back in eight hours.

00:22:29.610 --> 00:22:31.068 align:middle line:84%
But the baby doesn't
speak English.

00:22:31.068 --> 00:22:33.780 align:middle line:84%
So the baby's just thinking,
like, I'm dying, right?

00:22:33.780 --> 00:22:36.010 align:middle line:84%
And they cry itself
out until it sleeps.

00:22:36.010 --> 00:22:37.530 align:middle line:84%
But the problem is
that when you're

00:22:37.530 --> 00:22:40.830 align:middle line:84%
fired 35 years
later from your job

00:22:40.830 --> 00:22:45.150 align:middle line:84%
or when your boyfriend or
girlfriend cheats on you,

00:22:45.150 --> 00:22:48.060 align:middle line:84%
it reopens the primal
abandonment wound.

00:22:48.060 --> 00:22:52.080 align:middle line:84%
So my main interest
is how people

00:22:52.080 --> 00:22:54.600 align:middle line:84%
feel betrayed by
their own parents,

00:22:54.600 --> 00:22:57.925 align:middle line:84%
because it's all babies want
is to be loved unconditionally.

00:22:57.925 --> 00:22:58.800 align:middle line:90%
That's all they want.

00:22:58.800 --> 00:23:00.690 align:middle line:90%
They want to be safe.

00:23:00.690 --> 00:23:01.597 align:middle line:90%
They want to be held.

00:23:01.597 --> 00:23:02.430 align:middle line:90%
They want to be fed.

00:23:02.430 --> 00:23:03.810 align:middle line:90%
They want to be cleaned, right?

00:23:03.810 --> 00:23:05.460 align:middle line:90%
And in our culture--

00:23:05.460 --> 00:23:07.500 align:middle line:84%
you know, I have friends
who send their kids

00:23:07.500 --> 00:23:09.583 align:middle line:84%
to these schools
at two years old.

00:23:09.583 --> 00:23:12.000 align:middle line:84%
And they're like, yeah, they
have a really high acceptance

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:12.930 align:middle line:90%
rate for Harvard.

00:23:12.930 --> 00:23:15.060 align:middle line:84%
And I'm like, your kid
wants to play with clay.

00:23:15.060 --> 00:23:18.600 align:middle line:84%
Your kid is not concerned about
going to Harvard in 16 years.

00:23:18.600 --> 00:23:21.090 align:middle line:84%
Like, why are you putting
all this pressure, you know?

00:23:21.090 --> 00:23:24.660 align:middle line:84%
So there's a component of
our highly competitive brand

00:23:24.660 --> 00:23:28.240 align:middle line:84%
of capitalism, which has
influenced parenting.

00:23:28.240 --> 00:23:30.550 align:middle line:84%
And the other thing, as
I mentioned in our book,

00:23:30.550 --> 00:23:34.220 align:middle line:84%
parenting comes in
waves, ebbs and flows.

00:23:34.220 --> 00:23:36.880 align:middle line:84%
So after World War
II, what I noticed

00:23:36.880 --> 00:23:40.030 align:middle line:84%
was that parents
were really afraid

00:23:40.030 --> 00:23:45.060 align:middle line:84%
of the Cold War of Russia,
bombing, another Hitler.

00:23:45.060 --> 00:23:47.290 align:middle line:84%
They lived through all
this terrible stuff.

00:23:47.290 --> 00:23:52.390 align:middle line:84%
And so I find that a lot of
people in that generation

00:23:52.390 --> 00:23:59.560 align:middle line:84%
were emotionally withholding
and they had these conceptions

00:23:59.560 --> 00:24:02.860 align:middle line:84%
that if our kids become
doctors and lawyers,

00:24:02.860 --> 00:24:05.740 align:middle line:84%
then when the second Hilter
comes, we'll be ready.

00:24:05.740 --> 00:24:08.510 align:middle line:84%
They just had this whole
other thing happening.

00:24:08.510 --> 00:24:11.890 align:middle line:84%
And I also say in the book-- and
I'll say this right upfront--

00:24:11.890 --> 00:24:13.870 align:middle line:84%
you know, we have
to say, our parents

00:24:13.870 --> 00:24:18.193 align:middle line:84%
did the best that they could
with the tools that they had.

00:24:18.193 --> 00:24:20.110 align:middle line:84%
If you're walking around
blaming your parents,

00:24:20.110 --> 00:24:21.693 align:middle line:84%
you're only hurting
yourself, right?

00:24:21.693 --> 00:24:23.110 align:middle line:84%
They did the best
that they could.

00:24:23.110 --> 00:24:27.460 align:middle line:84%
Now, the irony is, if
parents want to really help

00:24:27.460 --> 00:24:30.470 align:middle line:84%
the growth of their children,
at some point in time,

00:24:30.470 --> 00:24:34.227 align:middle line:84%
they should say
something like this--

00:24:34.227 --> 00:24:35.310 align:middle line:90%
we could have done better.

00:24:35.310 --> 00:24:38.700 align:middle line:90%


00:24:38.700 --> 00:24:41.150 align:middle line:84%
So there's this-- like,
that's fascinating to me

00:24:41.150 --> 00:24:44.600 align:middle line:84%
that, for us, we have to
always say my parents did

00:24:44.600 --> 00:24:46.450 align:middle line:90%
the best that they could.

00:24:46.450 --> 00:24:49.520 align:middle line:84%
And the other thing that I
always take into account--

00:24:49.520 --> 00:24:53.000 align:middle line:84%
and I don't know how this
will go over, but it's karma.

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:54.740 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if you
believe in karma, then

00:24:54.740 --> 00:24:57.740 align:middle line:90%
you chose those people, right?

00:24:57.740 --> 00:25:01.257 align:middle line:90%
So that to me really helps.

00:25:01.257 --> 00:25:03.590 align:middle line:84%
I'll ask people-- if they
come in and they're just like,

00:25:03.590 --> 00:25:06.048 align:middle line:84%
this terrible thing happened,
this terrible thing happened,

00:25:06.048 --> 00:25:09.890 align:middle line:84%
and my father did this, my
mother did this, I'm like, OK.

00:25:09.890 --> 00:25:12.500 align:middle line:84%
When-- after it's all
over, I'll be like,

00:25:12.500 --> 00:25:14.540 align:middle line:84%
so why did your soul--
what did your soul

00:25:14.540 --> 00:25:17.310 align:middle line:84%
need to learn that they chose
to be incarnated by these two

00:25:17.310 --> 00:25:18.110 align:middle line:90%
people?

00:25:18.110 --> 00:25:20.910 align:middle line:90%


00:25:20.910 --> 00:25:26.860 align:middle line:84%
>> So you think part of the
process of deciphering meaning

00:25:26.860 --> 00:25:32.170 align:middle line:84%
out of having potentially
abusive parents is to question

00:25:32.170 --> 00:25:35.530 align:middle line:84%
in retrospect, what was I here
to learn from that experience?

00:25:35.530 --> 00:25:37.030 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, as I
mentioned in the book,

00:25:37.030 --> 00:25:38.470 align:middle line:90%
as we spoke about before--

00:25:38.470 --> 00:25:43.300 align:middle line:84%
so his holiness the Dalai Lama I
sat with at various conferences

00:25:43.300 --> 00:25:45.100 align:middle line:84%
and things, and
people say, you know,

00:25:45.100 --> 00:25:46.540 align:middle line:90%
who's your greatest teacher?

00:25:46.540 --> 00:25:50.740 align:middle line:84%
And as the spokesperson
for Buddhism in the West,

00:25:50.740 --> 00:25:54.670 align:middle line:84%
the answer has to be the
Buddha is my greatest teacher.

00:25:54.670 --> 00:25:55.930 align:middle line:90%
And what does he say?

00:25:55.930 --> 00:26:01.750 align:middle line:84%
The Chinese-- who bludgeoned
with ax handles two million

00:26:01.750 --> 00:26:04.660 align:middle line:90%
of his followers, right?

00:26:04.660 --> 00:26:06.520 align:middle line:90%
And that's his greatest teacher.

00:26:06.520 --> 00:26:11.510 align:middle line:84%
So for me, owning your life
means reframing it to say,

00:26:11.510 --> 00:26:13.150 align:middle line:90%
OK, I'm here today.

00:26:13.150 --> 00:26:14.530 align:middle line:90%
I'm safe.

00:26:14.530 --> 00:26:18.790 align:middle line:84%
Yes, my face was blown
off my head 33 years ago.

00:26:18.790 --> 00:26:21.220 align:middle line:84%
Yes, I had this
kind of relationship

00:26:21.220 --> 00:26:25.000 align:middle line:84%
with my parents or this
person or this was humiliating

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:26.080 align:middle line:90%
or this or something.

00:26:26.080 --> 00:26:29.200 align:middle line:84%
But instead of fighting
reality, a reality

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:31.240 align:middle line:84%
that you can't
change, the sooner

00:26:31.240 --> 00:26:33.700 align:middle line:84%
you own it is the
sooner you'll let

00:26:33.700 --> 00:26:36.280 align:middle line:90%
go of all those resentments.

00:26:36.280 --> 00:26:39.520 align:middle line:84%
And those resentments
are now the adage

00:26:39.520 --> 00:26:40.990 align:middle line:90%
from the 12-step program.

00:26:40.990 --> 00:26:42.910 align:middle line:84%
Resentment is like poking
yourself in the eye

00:26:42.910 --> 00:26:45.790 align:middle line:84%
and waiting for your
parents to go blind.

00:26:45.790 --> 00:26:48.340 align:middle line:84%
Resentment is like
drinking poison and waiting

00:26:48.340 --> 00:26:51.850 align:middle line:84%
for your older brother, who
kicked your ass every day,

00:26:51.850 --> 00:26:53.020 align:middle line:90%
to get sick.

00:26:53.020 --> 00:26:54.160 align:middle line:90%
He's not going to get sick.

00:26:54.160 --> 00:26:55.990 align:middle line:90%
You're only poisoning yourself.

00:26:55.990 --> 00:26:59.290 align:middle line:84%
So you have to forgive
all these people

00:26:59.290 --> 00:27:01.150 align:middle line:84%
and say they did
the best they could.

00:27:01.150 --> 00:27:04.390 align:middle line:84%
And listen, I know it's a hard
pill to swallow, you know?

00:27:04.390 --> 00:27:07.350 align:middle line:90%
It took me 25 years.

00:27:07.350 --> 00:27:12.490 align:middle line:84%
It's just like-- and when
the trauma is really close--

00:27:12.490 --> 00:27:19.580 align:middle line:84%
I know of a few people
who knew they were going

00:27:19.580 --> 00:27:24.630 align:middle line:84%
to be assaulted, and
they spoke to the person

00:27:24.630 --> 00:27:31.410 align:middle line:84%
who was about to do harm to
them and forgave them then.

00:27:31.410 --> 00:27:35.790 align:middle line:84%
But those people are a lot
more sophisticated than I am.

00:27:35.790 --> 00:27:38.192 align:middle line:90%


00:27:38.192 --> 00:27:39.900 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, I mean, I
think the Dalai Lama--

00:27:39.900 --> 00:27:41.550 align:middle line:90%
I mean, that's incredible.

00:27:41.550 --> 00:27:44.587 align:middle line:84%
For him to say something
like that is profound,

00:27:44.587 --> 00:27:46.170 align:middle line:84%
and I think it takes
someone like that

00:27:46.170 --> 00:27:48.670 align:middle line:90%
to say something like that.

00:27:48.670 --> 00:27:49.470 align:middle line:90%
Thanks for that.

00:27:49.470 --> 00:27:51.610 align:middle line:84%
I think we covered
that quite well.

00:27:51.610 --> 00:27:53.340 align:middle line:90%
>> I'll just-- one other thing.

00:27:53.340 --> 00:27:57.420 align:middle line:84%
So again, my whole
interest is consciousness

00:27:57.420 --> 00:27:58.320 align:middle line:90%
and the human mind.

00:27:58.320 --> 00:28:03.240 align:middle line:84%
I think that our primary desire
is to be loved unconditionally.

00:28:03.240 --> 00:28:05.280 align:middle line:84%
And we grew up in
this crazy society

00:28:05.280 --> 00:28:08.430 align:middle line:84%
which only gives us tools
to gain love conditionally.

00:28:08.430 --> 00:28:11.400 align:middle line:84%
So we're actually in this
giant resentment factory

00:28:11.400 --> 00:28:15.600 align:middle line:84%
because we can never have
what our hearts crave, right?

00:28:15.600 --> 00:28:18.690 align:middle line:84%
And I studied this
psychiatrist who

00:28:18.690 --> 00:28:21.220 align:middle line:84%
says that language,
even just talking,

00:28:21.220 --> 00:28:26.880 align:middle line:84%
estranges us from the
real phenomenon of being.

00:28:26.880 --> 00:28:29.130 align:middle line:84%
And that's really an
interesting concept,

00:28:29.130 --> 00:28:33.270 align:middle line:84%
because in America, Sonja
Lyubomirsky, who lives down

00:28:33.270 --> 00:28:35.910 align:middle line:84%
the street, she wrote a
book, "The How of Happiness,"

00:28:35.910 --> 00:28:38.010 align:middle line:84%
and she talks about
the Hedonic treadmill.

00:28:38.010 --> 00:28:39.960 align:middle line:84%
So all the things
that were taught

00:28:39.960 --> 00:28:43.860 align:middle line:84%
by social media and the
media that will make us happy

00:28:43.860 --> 00:28:45.090 align:middle line:90%
actually make us miserable.

00:28:45.090 --> 00:28:47.280 align:middle line:84%
And ironically, I
live in a culture

00:28:47.280 --> 00:28:50.140 align:middle line:84%
with the inalienable
right to pursue happiness.

00:28:50.140 --> 00:28:52.260 align:middle line:84%
And that is the worst
thing ever, right?

00:28:52.260 --> 00:28:54.930 align:middle line:90%
You cannot pursue happiness.

00:28:54.930 --> 00:28:57.510 align:middle line:90%
It's not-- it's a ramification.

00:28:57.510 --> 00:28:59.410 align:middle line:90%
Happiness is a byproduct.

00:28:59.410 --> 00:29:02.580 align:middle line:84%
So what you need to
do is sleep correctly,

00:29:02.580 --> 00:29:06.160 align:middle line:84%
have loving relationships,
eat well, get some exercise.

00:29:06.160 --> 00:29:07.390 align:middle line:90%
It's not brain surgery.

00:29:07.390 --> 00:29:09.600 align:middle line:84%
And yet 100 million
prescriptions

00:29:09.600 --> 00:29:12.570 align:middle line:84%
for antidepressants are
written in this country

00:29:12.570 --> 00:29:14.400 align:middle line:90%
of 330 million people.

00:29:14.400 --> 00:29:18.390 align:middle line:84%
22 million Americans take
antidepressants every day,

00:29:18.390 --> 00:29:20.820 align:middle line:84%
and I don't think it's
some rogue gene that

00:29:20.820 --> 00:29:22.170 align:middle line:90%
just afflicts Americans.

00:29:22.170 --> 00:29:24.280 align:middle line:84%
I think we need to look
at our school system.

00:29:24.280 --> 00:29:26.520 align:middle line:84%
We have to look at this
nuclear family or the

00:29:26.520 --> 00:29:29.450 align:middle line:84%
being raised by a
single mom or single dad

00:29:29.450 --> 00:29:32.190 align:middle line:84%
and then working 80 hours a
week and being proud of it.

00:29:32.190 --> 00:29:35.160 align:middle line:84%
I mean, this is an insane
time we're living in.

00:29:35.160 --> 00:29:36.360 align:middle line:90%
All of us have our phones.

00:29:36.360 --> 00:29:38.460 align:middle line:84%
Some of the times
they're under our pillows

00:29:38.460 --> 00:29:40.650 align:middle line:84%
I don't know anyone who
doesn't go to the bathroom

00:29:40.650 --> 00:29:43.590 align:middle line:84%
without an iPad or
something in there.

00:29:43.590 --> 00:29:45.930 align:middle line:84%
I mean, can you just have
those five minutes of,

00:29:45.930 --> 00:29:49.810 align:middle line:90%
like, you know, a little just--

00:29:49.810 --> 00:29:51.540 align:middle line:90%
it's crazy, right?

00:29:51.540 --> 00:29:54.030 align:middle line:84%
If aliens came down
and looked at--

00:29:54.030 --> 00:29:56.340 align:middle line:84%
just they went into
Abbot Kinney where

00:29:56.340 --> 00:29:58.252 align:middle line:84%
you were yesterday
in Intelligentsia

00:29:58.252 --> 00:30:00.210 align:middle line:84%
and looked at everyone
with their sunglasses on

00:30:00.210 --> 00:30:00.990 align:middle line:90%
and their iPods--

00:30:00.990 --> 00:30:02.010 align:middle line:90%
no one's looking at each other.

00:30:02.010 --> 00:30:03.030 align:middle line:90%
You can't say anything.

00:30:03.030 --> 00:30:04.070 align:middle line:90%
They're frowning.

00:30:04.070 --> 00:30:06.240 align:middle line:84%
They're like-- they're
paying $8 for coffee.

00:30:06.240 --> 00:30:08.550 align:middle line:84%
I mean, like, none of
this makes sense, right?

00:30:08.550 --> 00:30:11.330 align:middle line:90%
I mean-- and we do it every day.

00:30:11.330 --> 00:30:13.180 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:30:13.180 --> 00:30:13.980 align:middle line:90%
You're right.

00:30:13.980 --> 00:30:16.310 align:middle line:90%
I mean, we've designed--

00:30:16.310 --> 00:30:17.680 align:middle line:90%
OK, maybe a deeper question.

00:30:17.680 --> 00:30:20.640 align:middle line:84%
I don't know if you're
willing to answer this.

00:30:20.640 --> 00:30:23.940 align:middle line:84%
This system we designed
around education--

00:30:23.940 --> 00:30:27.030 align:middle line:84%
primary education,
secondary, college, whatever

00:30:27.030 --> 00:30:30.780 align:middle line:90%
we call it between countries--

00:30:30.780 --> 00:30:36.540 align:middle line:84%
this capitalistic consumerist
society and this produced GDP,

00:30:36.540 --> 00:30:38.970 align:middle line:84%
produced economic output at
any cost-- think about it.

00:30:38.970 --> 00:30:40.740 align:middle line:84%
We measure a company--
a country's success

00:30:40.740 --> 00:30:41.580 align:middle line:90%
on GDP, right?

00:30:41.580 --> 00:30:43.006 align:middle line:90%
>> Which is a fiction.

00:30:43.006 --> 00:30:44.000 align:middle line:90%
>> True.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:44.220 align:middle line:90%
And--

00:30:44.220 --> 00:30:46.000 align:middle line:84%
>> It has no
correlation to anything.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:46.800 align:middle line:90%
>> No.

00:30:46.800 --> 00:30:49.350 align:middle line:84%
But if there's a mother at
home looking after a child,

00:30:49.350 --> 00:30:51.150 align:middle line:84%
there's no economic
output for that.

00:30:51.150 --> 00:30:52.920 align:middle line:84%
If she goes back
into the workforce

00:30:52.920 --> 00:30:55.540 align:middle line:84%
and puts her child in daycare,
it's a double economic output.

00:30:55.540 --> 00:30:56.580 align:middle line:84%
There's money going
into the daycare.

00:30:56.580 --> 00:30:57.997 align:middle line:84%
There's money
coming from the job.

00:30:57.997 --> 00:31:01.950 align:middle line:84%
>> One of the greatest
contributing factors to GDP is

00:31:01.950 --> 00:31:04.930 align:middle line:90%
car accidents.

00:31:04.930 --> 00:31:06.900 align:middle line:84%
There's really
terrible things that

00:31:06.900 --> 00:31:09.450 align:middle line:84%
contribute to our
domestic product

00:31:09.450 --> 00:31:11.985 align:middle line:84%
in terms of, like, things
being destroyed and ambulances

00:31:11.985 --> 00:31:13.610 align:middle line:84%
and all the billion
dollar industries--

00:31:13.610 --> 00:31:14.940 align:middle line:90%
I'm sure pornography.

00:31:14.940 --> 00:31:17.400 align:middle line:84%
Like, there's-- like, GDP
is a stupid measurement.

00:31:17.400 --> 00:31:21.480 align:middle line:84%
It's funny because there was
a debate last Friday night

00:31:21.480 --> 00:31:23.820 align:middle line:84%
between Slavoj Zizek, the
philosopher, and Jordan

00:31:23.820 --> 00:31:24.840 align:middle line:90%
Peterson.

00:31:24.840 --> 00:31:29.460 align:middle line:84%
And it's-- the problem I see
now is that we're not having

00:31:29.460 --> 00:31:30.690 align:middle line:90%
the right conversations.

00:31:30.690 --> 00:31:33.270 align:middle line:84%
When you have people
arguing about GDP

00:31:33.270 --> 00:31:34.860 align:middle line:84%
and how this is
happening and there's

00:31:34.860 --> 00:31:38.820 align:middle line:84%
been this type of growth,
you're not on the ground

00:31:38.820 --> 00:31:44.280 align:middle line:84%
sitting there with the
workers from Walmart or Amazon

00:31:44.280 --> 00:31:47.020 align:middle line:84%
who don't have health
insurance who are on welfare.

00:31:47.020 --> 00:31:49.920 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we have these
bullshit statistics

00:31:49.920 --> 00:31:53.790 align:middle line:84%
that people use to
buttress arguments

00:31:53.790 --> 00:31:56.100 align:middle line:84%
so that the rich get richer
and the poor get poorer.

00:31:56.100 --> 00:31:59.560 align:middle line:84%
But really we need
equality of opportunity

00:31:59.560 --> 00:32:02.017 align:middle line:84%
so that people have a fair
shot of going to college.

00:32:02.017 --> 00:32:03.600 align:middle line:84%
They don't have to
bribe their way in,

00:32:03.600 --> 00:32:05.808 align:middle line:84%
like we've just had all
these terrible scandals here.

00:32:05.808 --> 00:32:07.290 align:middle line:84%
But, really, Jewish
people were not

00:32:07.290 --> 00:32:09.870 align:middle line:84%
allowed at Harvard
University until the 1920s.

00:32:09.870 --> 00:32:11.160 align:middle line:90%
That's 300 years.

00:32:11.160 --> 00:32:13.530 align:middle line:90%
We have terrible misogyny.

00:32:13.530 --> 00:32:15.460 align:middle line:90%
We have terrible racism.

00:32:15.460 --> 00:32:18.050 align:middle line:84%
This country is just
full of hypocrites.

00:32:18.050 --> 00:32:21.417 align:middle line:84%
I mean, and it's the best
country in the world.

00:32:21.417 --> 00:32:22.250 align:middle line:90%
I mean, I live here.

00:32:22.250 --> 00:32:23.000 align:middle line:90%
I could live any place.

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:23.900 align:middle line:90%
I live here.

00:32:23.900 --> 00:32:26.580 align:middle line:84%
I enjoy the freedoms, free
speech, things like that.

00:32:26.580 --> 00:32:28.700 align:middle line:84%
But if you really look
at the systems in place,

00:32:28.700 --> 00:32:31.760 align:middle line:84%
the myth of romantic
love and the money

00:32:31.760 --> 00:32:35.630 align:middle line:84%
swirling around
marriages and divorces,

00:32:35.630 --> 00:32:38.050 align:middle line:84%
I mean, these are
businesses, man.

00:32:38.050 --> 00:32:39.410 align:middle line:90%
There's a lot of money, right?

00:32:39.410 --> 00:32:41.990 align:middle line:84%
And then all the heartbreak--
and then people like me,

00:32:41.990 --> 00:32:44.000 align:middle line:84%
psychotherapists,
marriage counselors,

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:46.520 align:middle line:90%
who people sign up for life.

00:32:46.520 --> 00:32:48.020 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I make the
joke in the book.

00:32:48.020 --> 00:32:50.960 align:middle line:84%
I said, marriage for
life was a fantastic idea

00:32:50.960 --> 00:32:53.720 align:middle line:84%
in the 13th century when
people lived to be 28.

00:32:53.720 --> 00:32:56.030 align:middle line:84%
But now that we're
living until 87,

00:32:56.030 --> 00:32:57.890 align:middle line:84%
we should have renewable
marriage contracts.

00:32:57.890 --> 00:33:00.182 align:middle line:84%
On your anniversary, you
should sit down and say, well,

00:33:00.182 --> 00:33:01.760 align:middle line:90%
what'd you like this year?

00:33:01.760 --> 00:33:02.970 align:middle line:90%
What didn't you like?

00:33:02.970 --> 00:33:04.070 align:middle line:90%
OK, I can do better.

00:33:04.070 --> 00:33:05.670 align:middle line:90%
I'll sign on again, right?

00:33:05.670 --> 00:33:06.470 align:middle line:90%
If you have a kid--

00:33:06.470 --> 00:33:07.370 align:middle line:90%
18 years.

00:33:07.370 --> 00:33:09.260 align:middle line:84%
These are just
commonsensical things.

00:33:09.260 --> 00:33:13.220 align:middle line:84%
But we live on this whole
other paradigm of Christianity,

00:33:13.220 --> 00:33:15.080 align:middle line:84%
marriage for life,
and we really need

00:33:15.080 --> 00:33:17.960 align:middle line:84%
to rethink our government,
the way we're interacting,

00:33:17.960 --> 00:33:21.640 align:middle line:90%
and our work-life balance.

00:33:21.640 --> 00:33:22.460 align:middle line:90%
>> True.

00:33:22.460 --> 00:33:23.712 align:middle line:90%
I agree.

00:33:23.712 --> 00:33:25.670 align:middle line:84%
There was an acronym you
mentioned in the book,

00:33:25.670 --> 00:33:27.150 align:middle line:90%
and I think it was--

00:33:27.150 --> 00:33:27.950 align:middle line:90%
>> WEIRD.

00:33:27.950 --> 00:33:30.200 align:middle line:90%
>> WEIRD.

00:33:30.200 --> 00:33:31.490 align:middle line:90%
What does that stand for?

00:33:31.490 --> 00:33:32.730 align:middle line:90%
And what does it mean?

00:33:32.730 --> 00:33:34.710 align:middle line:84%
And maybe, if you
want to riff on this,

00:33:34.710 --> 00:33:40.100 align:middle line:84%
how did we get into
this area of these goals

00:33:40.100 --> 00:33:41.660 align:middle line:84%
that we're all
striving for and how

00:33:41.660 --> 00:33:44.035 align:middle line:84%
we're sort of missing the
happiness boat because of that?

00:33:44.035 --> 00:33:46.560 align:middle line:84%
So the first, the acronym,
what does it stand for?

00:33:46.560 --> 00:33:47.360 align:middle line:90%
What is it?

00:33:47.360 --> 00:33:51.500 align:middle line:84%
>> Ironically, we live in
a society that could be

00:33:51.500 --> 00:33:53.900 align:middle line:90%
identified by the acronym WEIRD.

00:33:53.900 --> 00:33:57.770 align:middle line:84%
We're Western, educated,
industrialized, rich,

00:33:57.770 --> 00:33:58.730 align:middle line:90%
and democratic.

00:33:58.730 --> 00:34:01.190 align:middle line:84%
Now, the interesting
thing in terms of the DSM,

00:34:01.190 --> 00:34:04.640 align:middle line:84%
the Diagnostic Statistical
Manual of Disorders,

00:34:04.640 --> 00:34:12.409 align:middle line:84%
is that we inflict our diagnoses
on the rest of the world.

00:34:12.409 --> 00:34:15.889 align:middle line:84%
But, actually, WEIRD
populations are only 12%

00:34:15.889 --> 00:34:20.580 align:middle line:90%
of the entire world society.

00:34:20.580 --> 00:34:25.550 align:middle line:84%
So the reason I like to
talk about these things

00:34:25.550 --> 00:34:30.050 align:middle line:84%
is because Thomas Kuhn
in 1968 wrote a book

00:34:30.050 --> 00:34:34.110 align:middle line:84%
and talked about paradigm
shifting every 25 years.

00:34:34.110 --> 00:34:39.469 align:middle line:84%
So if you look at the DSM, there
was a "New York Times" article

00:34:39.469 --> 00:34:45.800 align:middle line:84%
about 13 years ago that stated
that 56% of the psychiatrist

00:34:45.800 --> 00:34:47.810 align:middle line:84%
who wrote for the
DSM had taken money

00:34:47.810 --> 00:34:49.739 align:middle line:90%
from pharmaceutical companies.

00:34:49.739 --> 00:34:51.350 align:middle line:90%
So there's this component.

00:34:51.350 --> 00:34:53.900 align:middle line:84%
And I'm not going into some
kind of conspiracy theory.

00:34:53.900 --> 00:34:57.500 align:middle line:84%
I'm just saying that people
benefit from other people being

00:34:57.500 --> 00:34:58.700 align:middle line:90%
diagnosed.

00:34:58.700 --> 00:35:01.700 align:middle line:84%
So as a psychotherapist,
I avoid diagnoses

00:35:01.700 --> 00:35:03.920 align:middle line:84%
because those labels
confine people.

00:35:03.920 --> 00:35:05.630 align:middle line:84%
And people get into
this whole thing

00:35:05.630 --> 00:35:08.330 align:middle line:84%
where I feel they're
terribly disempowered.

00:35:08.330 --> 00:35:11.090 align:middle line:84%
If you say, oh yeah,
my mother is bipolar

00:35:11.090 --> 00:35:13.370 align:middle line:84%
and her mother is bipolar
and everyone's bipolar

00:35:13.370 --> 00:35:15.770 align:middle line:84%
so I have to be on these
medications, that's

00:35:15.770 --> 00:35:17.060 align:middle line:90%
very disempowering.

00:35:17.060 --> 00:35:19.610 align:middle line:84%
There's no solution
but that pill.

00:35:19.610 --> 00:35:26.900 align:middle line:84%
For me, if you say, yeah, I'm
a human being and occasionally

00:35:26.900 --> 00:35:29.750 align:middle line:84%
I have these emotions
that are highly unpleasant

00:35:29.750 --> 00:35:32.780 align:middle line:84%
and I'm going to try to
find a solution to that

00:35:32.780 --> 00:35:35.660 align:middle line:90%
that is not some kind of pill--

00:35:35.660 --> 00:35:37.400 align:middle line:84%
and listen, I work
with schizophrenics.

00:35:37.400 --> 00:35:40.550 align:middle line:84%
I work with severely
challenged people,

00:35:40.550 --> 00:35:43.640 align:middle line:84%
and they need to be medicated,
too, so that they don't do harm

00:35:43.640 --> 00:35:46.830 align:middle line:84%
to themselves or other people
or can function in society.

00:35:46.830 --> 00:35:50.540 align:middle line:84%
However, not everybody
who just wants to--

00:35:50.540 --> 00:35:53.900 align:middle line:84%
like, these kids today,
they're on ADHD medication.

00:35:53.900 --> 00:35:57.360 align:middle line:84%
They have this game
that they play.

00:35:57.360 --> 00:35:58.970 align:middle line:84%
And it's really
our school system.

00:35:58.970 --> 00:36:02.090 align:middle line:84%
Our school system was
developed to make workers.

00:36:02.090 --> 00:36:05.000 align:middle line:84%
Not everybody needs to study
chemistry, and yet in America

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:06.380 align:middle line:90%
everyone studies chemistry.

00:36:06.380 --> 00:36:09.590 align:middle line:84%
Not everyone should be studying
art if you need to be this.

00:36:09.590 --> 00:36:11.455 align:middle line:84%
And we just force
these kids, and then

00:36:11.455 --> 00:36:13.580 align:middle line:84%
if they don't like the
stuff that they're studying,

00:36:13.580 --> 00:36:17.370 align:middle line:84%
we dope them up on this,
like, cocaine-like substance,

00:36:17.370 --> 00:36:18.950 align:middle line:90%
this amphetamine, you know?

00:36:18.950 --> 00:36:21.260 align:middle line:84%
And I have these
kids in my office,

00:36:21.260 --> 00:36:23.560 align:middle line:84%
and they can play
this trick on doctors.

00:36:23.560 --> 00:36:25.620 align:middle line:90%
They go into the doctor office.

00:36:25.620 --> 00:36:28.340 align:middle line:84%
They're like, I find
myself looking out

00:36:28.340 --> 00:36:30.977 align:middle line:90%
the window in blank class.

00:36:30.977 --> 00:36:32.810 align:middle line:84%
And the doctor just--
there was this article

00:36:32.810 --> 00:36:37.520 align:middle line:84%
where, like, doctors were
seeing patients, kids, for seven

00:36:37.520 --> 00:36:40.400 align:middle line:84%
minutes and just
prescribing ADHD medication.

00:36:40.400 --> 00:36:42.770 align:middle line:84%
And then the kids
can't sleep, and then

00:36:42.770 --> 00:36:45.140 align:middle line:84%
there's this whole
cycle of craziness,

00:36:45.140 --> 00:36:48.380 align:middle line:84%
and they start really young,
like, 7, 8, 9 years old.

00:36:48.380 --> 00:36:50.000 align:middle line:90%
They don't need medication.

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:51.290 align:middle line:90%
These kids need hugs.

00:36:51.290 --> 00:36:52.730 align:middle line:90%
They need to go play baseball.

00:36:52.730 --> 00:36:54.400 align:middle line:90%
They need to play with dolls.

00:36:54.400 --> 00:36:57.770 align:middle line:84%
And we live in this culture
that's so competitive.

00:36:57.770 --> 00:37:00.440 align:middle line:84%
It's a win or take all
society, and everybody

00:37:00.440 --> 00:37:03.230 align:middle line:84%
wants to be Bill Gates
or Angelina Jolie

00:37:03.230 --> 00:37:05.643 align:middle line:84%
or somebody who's on a
kiosk, but they don't really,

00:37:05.643 --> 00:37:08.060 align:middle line:84%
because you don't want to have
Asperger's like Bill Gates,

00:37:08.060 --> 00:37:10.250 align:middle line:84%
and you don't want to have a
double mastectomy like Angelina

00:37:10.250 --> 00:37:11.050 align:middle line:90%
Jolie.

00:37:11.050 --> 00:37:15.360 align:middle line:84%
You just want to have her $400
million or his $36 billion.

00:37:15.360 --> 00:37:19.870 align:middle line:84%
But if we explain to people
that doesn't make you happier,

00:37:19.870 --> 00:37:21.760 align:middle line:84%
you just have a different
set of problems.

00:37:21.760 --> 00:37:23.740 align:middle line:84%
Bill-- there was an
article last week.

00:37:23.740 --> 00:37:27.190 align:middle line:84%
Mark Zuckerberg last
year spent $22 million

00:37:27.190 --> 00:37:31.330 align:middle line:84%
to not have his family
harmed, $22 million.

00:37:31.330 --> 00:37:34.180 align:middle line:84%
You could feed a small country
in Africa for that money.

00:37:34.180 --> 00:37:37.000 align:middle line:90%
He can't go to Intelligentsia.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:38.860 align:middle line:90%
He can't go out of the house.

00:37:38.860 --> 00:37:39.980 align:middle line:90%
He can't do anything.

00:37:39.980 --> 00:37:42.260 align:middle line:84%
There's a militia
around Bill Gates.

00:37:42.260 --> 00:37:45.490 align:middle line:84%
When Bill Gates goes some
place to speak, it's like--

00:37:45.490 --> 00:37:49.220 align:middle line:84%
there's this whole-- the bomb
sweeping and all this crazy

00:37:49.220 --> 00:37:50.020 align:middle line:90%
stuff.

00:37:50.020 --> 00:37:52.540 align:middle line:84%
And then you look
at these kids today.

00:37:52.540 --> 00:37:54.370 align:middle line:84%
What do you want to
do when you grow up?

00:37:54.370 --> 00:37:55.720 align:middle line:90%
I want to be Bill Gates.

00:37:55.720 --> 00:37:56.890 align:middle line:90%
No, you don't.

00:37:56.890 --> 00:37:58.270 align:middle line:84%
You don't want to
have a militia.

00:37:58.270 --> 00:38:00.760 align:middle line:84%
You want to go walk on the
beach and jump in the ocean.

00:38:00.760 --> 00:38:03.460 align:middle line:84%
You don't want to
have 50 guys with guns

00:38:03.460 --> 00:38:08.200 align:middle line:84%
strapped all over them so
that you can get an ice cream.

00:38:08.200 --> 00:38:09.560 align:middle line:90%
>> Right?

00:38:09.560 --> 00:38:10.360 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:38:10.360 --> 00:38:11.710 align:middle line:90%
I think one of the really--

00:38:11.710 --> 00:38:13.450 align:middle line:84%
one of the most profound
things that happened to me when

00:38:13.450 --> 00:38:14.980 align:middle line:84%
I'm young-- and I'm so
grateful for all the

00:38:14.980 --> 00:38:16.397 align:middle line:84%
experiences in my
life, and I feel

00:38:16.397 --> 00:38:19.900 align:middle line:84%
that I've been given
mentors in my life

00:38:19.900 --> 00:38:22.660 align:middle line:84%
to teach me about
experiences very early on.

00:38:22.660 --> 00:38:25.120 align:middle line:84%
And Laurentine's godfather
was a big mentor of mine,

00:38:25.120 --> 00:38:26.710 align:middle line:90%
big in Siddhi Yoga.

00:38:26.710 --> 00:38:29.410 align:middle line:84%
And his message he
got from the guru

00:38:29.410 --> 00:38:33.790 align:middle line:84%
was multifaceted,
that one was, if you

00:38:33.790 --> 00:38:37.480 align:middle line:90%
see duality, laugh at it.

00:38:37.480 --> 00:38:39.790 align:middle line:84%
Experience oneness
in everything.

00:38:39.790 --> 00:38:41.430 align:middle line:90%
And be grateful for this life.

00:38:41.430 --> 00:38:42.700 align:middle line:90%
That was his three boons.

00:38:42.700 --> 00:38:43.660 align:middle line:90%
Super profound.

00:38:43.660 --> 00:38:46.990 align:middle line:84%
Then another gentleman
in a similar sort of--

00:38:46.990 --> 00:38:52.360 align:middle line:84%
he was also involved in
the same lineage of yoga--

00:38:52.360 --> 00:38:54.110 align:middle line:90%
was taught this message.

00:38:54.110 --> 00:38:54.910 align:middle line:90%
And I sort of--

00:38:54.910 --> 00:38:57.340 align:middle line:84%
I've stolen both of their
messages for myself--

00:38:57.340 --> 00:38:59.200 align:middle line:90%
borrowed, should we say.

00:38:59.200 --> 00:39:03.040 align:middle line:84%
Everything is absolutely
always unfolding perfectly,

00:39:03.040 --> 00:39:05.022 align:middle line:90%
not for a reason, good or bad.

00:39:05.022 --> 00:39:06.730 align:middle line:84%
That was-- this happened
for that reason.

00:39:06.730 --> 00:39:07.900 align:middle line:90%
That was bad, you know?

00:39:07.900 --> 00:39:09.190 align:middle line:84%
But that everything
is absolutely always

00:39:09.190 --> 00:39:10.023 align:middle line:90%
unfolding perfectly.

00:39:10.023 --> 00:39:11.710 align:middle line:84%
So it's perfection
in everything.

00:39:11.710 --> 00:39:16.390 align:middle line:84%
That's really helped me move
faster through trauma or issues

00:39:16.390 --> 00:39:18.640 align:middle line:84%
because I'm like, what is
seeking to emerge from this?

00:39:18.640 --> 00:39:20.980 align:middle line:84%
What is the perfection
seeking to emerge from this?

00:39:20.980 --> 00:39:23.440 align:middle line:84%
I also worked for two
of the wealthiest people

00:39:23.440 --> 00:39:27.500 align:middle line:84%
in the world, one involved in a
similar company, the person you

00:39:27.500 --> 00:39:28.300 align:middle line:90%
just mentioned.

00:39:28.300 --> 00:39:29.800 align:middle line:84%
I used to drive
their private yacht.

00:39:29.800 --> 00:39:32.230 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that was a
previous career of mine.

00:39:32.230 --> 00:39:36.040 align:middle line:84%
And what I learned is that
money doesn't make you healthy,

00:39:36.040 --> 00:39:38.440 align:middle line:84%
and money doesn't
make you happy.

00:39:38.440 --> 00:39:41.187 align:middle line:84%
So why have we got all these
goals that we're aiming for?

00:39:41.187 --> 00:39:42.770 align:middle line:84%
And they're ultimately
not good goals.

00:39:42.770 --> 00:39:46.600 align:middle line:84%
Like, I live also in a
developing country called

00:39:46.600 --> 00:39:48.820 align:middle line:84%
Vanuatu, and Vanuatu
actually placed

00:39:48.820 --> 00:39:53.600 align:middle line:84%
number one on the Happy Person
Index, the HPI, in 2016.

00:39:53.600 --> 00:39:54.400 align:middle line:90%
>> Congratulations.

00:39:54.400 --> 00:39:54.940 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, thank you.

00:39:54.940 --> 00:39:56.020 align:middle line:90%
>> So what do you think it is?

00:39:56.020 --> 00:39:56.820 align:middle line:90%
>> I'm a resident.

00:39:56.820 --> 00:39:59.130 align:middle line:84%
I'm not a national
of that country.

00:39:59.130 --> 00:40:00.450 align:middle line:90%
>> They only polled James.

00:40:00.450 --> 00:40:01.680 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, no.

00:40:01.680 --> 00:40:03.400 align:middle line:84%
I was not living
there at the time.

00:40:03.400 --> 00:40:07.270 align:middle line:84%
But if-- I think Bhutan was one
of the first winners, right?

00:40:07.270 --> 00:40:09.820 align:middle line:84%
And then it's been tracked,
and people question the index.

00:40:09.820 --> 00:40:12.320 align:middle line:84%
But still they're trying to
measure some form of happiness.

00:40:12.320 --> 00:40:16.750 align:middle line:84%
So they won in 2016, and
it is just almost comical

00:40:16.750 --> 00:40:18.020 align:middle line:90%
how happy they are.

00:40:18.020 --> 00:40:20.170 align:middle line:84%
And you'll be driving to
school in the morning,

00:40:20.170 --> 00:40:21.460 align:middle line:84%
and there's a pickup
truck in front,

00:40:21.460 --> 00:40:22.900 align:middle line:84%
and they're all standing in
the back, all these guys,

00:40:22.900 --> 00:40:23.860 align:middle line:90%
laughing and singing.

00:40:23.860 --> 00:40:24.880 align:middle line:90%
Then it rains.

00:40:24.880 --> 00:40:26.213 align:middle line:90%
And they're getting drenched.

00:40:26.213 --> 00:40:27.880 align:middle line:84%
And it's 6:30, 7
o'clock in the morning.

00:40:27.880 --> 00:40:29.630 align:middle line:84%
And they're singing,
and they're laughing,

00:40:29.630 --> 00:40:32.370 align:middle line:84%
and a friend will jump off the
truck and nearly trip over,

00:40:32.370 --> 00:40:34.000 align:middle line:84%
and they laugh, and
they're laughing.

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:35.050 align:middle line:90%
They're all high fiving.

00:40:35.050 --> 00:40:36.790 align:middle line:90%
They're just ecstatic.

00:40:36.790 --> 00:40:39.220 align:middle line:84%
These guys live in a
shared home, like, eight

00:40:39.220 --> 00:40:40.870 align:middle line:90%
or 10 other people.

00:40:40.870 --> 00:40:42.760 align:middle line:90%
They own next to nothing.

00:40:42.760 --> 00:40:44.710 align:middle line:84%
They maybe go to
church or some religion

00:40:44.710 --> 00:40:46.720 align:middle line:84%
or some form of
meditation or practice

00:40:46.720 --> 00:40:49.240 align:middle line:84%
towards some higher
power once a week.

00:40:49.240 --> 00:40:50.450 align:middle line:90%
They respect each other.

00:40:50.450 --> 00:40:51.880 align:middle line:90%
They have a chief system.

00:40:51.880 --> 00:40:54.520 align:middle line:84%
They have no poverty
in their country

00:40:54.520 --> 00:40:57.820 align:middle line:84%
because everyone has food
and shelter because you're

00:40:57.820 --> 00:41:00.340 align:middle line:84%
a chief system and there's
food growing everywhere.

00:41:00.340 --> 00:41:01.400 align:middle line:90%
They're so happy.

00:41:01.400 --> 00:41:03.370 align:middle line:84%
And then I fly in and
out of that country

00:41:03.370 --> 00:41:07.690 align:middle line:84%
to, like, LA, New York,
packed European cities

00:41:07.690 --> 00:41:09.730 align:middle line:84%
with this congestion
issue and immigration.

00:41:09.730 --> 00:41:13.030 align:middle line:84%
Then I go to Australia, which
is also amazing but also stuck

00:41:13.030 --> 00:41:16.530 align:middle line:84%
under this whole rule of,
like, own your own home.

00:41:16.530 --> 00:41:18.012 align:middle line:90%
That's the Australian dream.

00:41:18.012 --> 00:41:20.470 align:middle line:84%
And people are stressed out,
putting their kids in daycare.

00:41:20.470 --> 00:41:22.850 align:middle line:84%
Even though it's a free and
happy country like America,

00:41:22.850 --> 00:41:26.680 align:middle line:84%
it's still there's this
oppressive sort of systems that

00:41:26.680 --> 00:41:28.180 align:middle line:84%
are just driving
us down, and you've

00:41:28.180 --> 00:41:30.490 align:middle line:84%
got this country stuck
in the middle of nowhere,

00:41:30.490 --> 00:41:31.290 align:middle line:90%
happy as Larry.

00:41:31.290 --> 00:41:32.090 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:41:32.090 --> 00:41:32.900 align:middle line:90%
>> Why?

00:41:32.900 --> 00:41:33.700 align:middle line:90%
How?

00:41:33.700 --> 00:41:34.700 align:middle line:90%
What's going on?

00:41:34.700 --> 00:41:36.910 align:middle line:84%
And how do we solve
these problems?

00:41:36.910 --> 00:41:39.790 align:middle line:84%
>> Again, I don't want to go
into somewhat of intentional

00:41:39.790 --> 00:41:41.080 align:middle line:90%
conspiracy theory.

00:41:41.080 --> 00:41:44.440 align:middle line:84%
But what's manifested since
the 1950s when America was

00:41:44.440 --> 00:41:47.410 align:middle line:84%
primarily a middle-class
society is that--

00:41:47.410 --> 00:41:50.110 align:middle line:84%
and I hope that you got this
from my book-- but power

00:41:50.110 --> 00:41:51.250 align:middle line:90%
corrupts.

00:41:51.250 --> 00:41:56.440 align:middle line:84%
And the four-- the founding
fathers of our society

00:41:56.440 --> 00:41:58.490 align:middle line:90%
didn't take that into account.

00:41:58.490 --> 00:42:02.740 align:middle line:84%
So every system has been
corrupted by the people

00:42:02.740 --> 00:42:04.660 align:middle line:90%
on top for their own benefit--

00:42:04.660 --> 00:42:09.580 align:middle line:84%
I mean, our taxation system,
the school system, the board

00:42:09.580 --> 00:42:12.020 align:middle line:90%
of directors, all these--

00:42:12.020 --> 00:42:13.870 align:middle line:84%
of companies and
things like that.

00:42:13.870 --> 00:42:16.630 align:middle line:90%
And we need to figure out--

00:42:16.630 --> 00:42:20.200 align:middle line:84%
it's been really fascinating
to watch people say, you know,

00:42:20.200 --> 00:42:22.090 align:middle line:90%
I want a free market society.

00:42:22.090 --> 00:42:24.430 align:middle line:84%
And as I say in the book,
a free market society

00:42:24.430 --> 00:42:27.260 align:middle line:84%
means that you say, here, you
want to buy these carrots,

00:42:27.260 --> 00:42:29.260 align:middle line:84%
and I stab you in the
neck and take the carrots.

00:42:29.260 --> 00:42:30.400 align:middle line:90%
That's a free market.

00:42:30.400 --> 00:42:33.160 align:middle line:84%
But we have regulations against
murder, against robbery,

00:42:33.160 --> 00:42:34.520 align:middle line:90%
against all these things.

00:42:34.520 --> 00:42:38.570 align:middle line:84%
And we've become
anti-authoritarian

00:42:38.570 --> 00:42:39.490 align:middle line:90%
in our culture.

00:42:39.490 --> 00:42:42.790 align:middle line:84%
For America, it's been
since Ronald Reagan.

00:42:42.790 --> 00:42:43.590 align:middle line:90%
Big government.

00:42:43.590 --> 00:42:45.430 align:middle line:90%
Government's bad, you know?

00:42:45.430 --> 00:42:47.920 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I tell people, if you
don't like big government,

00:42:47.920 --> 00:42:53.500 align:middle line:84%
don't live in a country with
330 million people and 300

00:42:53.500 --> 00:42:58.780 align:middle line:84%
million guns because someone's
got to protect us from those--

00:42:58.780 --> 00:43:01.510 align:middle line:84%
that situation because
it's not tenable.

00:43:01.510 --> 00:43:03.670 align:middle line:84%
It's not sustainable
because people get angry

00:43:03.670 --> 00:43:05.680 align:middle line:84%
and they shoot their
guns, you know?

00:43:05.680 --> 00:43:12.290 align:middle line:84%
So for me we have to figure
out a way to account for this--

00:43:12.290 --> 00:43:14.140 align:middle line:90%
I don't know what to call it--

00:43:14.140 --> 00:43:16.410 align:middle line:90%
because it's not an aberration.

00:43:16.410 --> 00:43:22.510 align:middle line:84%
When you become WEIRD, rich
like this, there's this envy.

00:43:22.510 --> 00:43:27.400 align:middle line:84%
There's this craziness
where you always project--

00:43:27.400 --> 00:43:30.130 align:middle line:84%
like with social media,
you measure your insides

00:43:30.130 --> 00:43:31.750 align:middle line:90%
by other people's outsides.

00:43:31.750 --> 00:43:35.080 align:middle line:84%
So you see them and you're
like, wow, they're happy

00:43:35.080 --> 00:43:36.730 align:middle line:90%
and they're smoking crack.

00:43:36.730 --> 00:43:37.960 align:middle line:90%
Like, I should smoke crack.

00:43:37.960 --> 00:43:41.350 align:middle line:84%
Or they have a Bentley
or they do whatever.

00:43:41.350 --> 00:43:44.360 align:middle line:84%
And you just-- your mind
does this crazy stuff.

00:43:44.360 --> 00:43:48.250 align:middle line:84%
So then for me what
I teach i s have

00:43:48.250 --> 00:43:51.760 align:middle line:84%
to be able to cultivate
non-reactivity, which

00:43:51.760 --> 00:43:54.940 align:middle line:84%
we do through meditation,
and understand

00:43:54.940 --> 00:44:01.590 align:middle line:84%
that your mind was devised
to give you bad information.

00:44:01.590 --> 00:44:05.230 align:middle line:84%
But it starts with wanting
to be loved unconditionally.

00:44:05.230 --> 00:44:09.100 align:middle line:90%
And then your mind--

00:44:09.100 --> 00:44:12.510 align:middle line:84%
the way it reacts to
traumas when you're a kid,

00:44:12.510 --> 00:44:13.720 align:middle line:90%
it's twofold.

00:44:13.720 --> 00:44:16.930 align:middle line:84%
Firstly, it says, wow,
that was humiliating.

00:44:16.930 --> 00:44:18.910 align:middle line:84%
I will never let
that happen again.

00:44:18.910 --> 00:44:20.230 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to do this.

00:44:20.230 --> 00:44:25.360 align:middle line:84%
And then you are this thing,
this facade, this persona

00:44:25.360 --> 00:44:27.100 align:middle line:90%
for the next 70 years.

00:44:27.100 --> 00:44:29.530 align:middle line:84%
And what I tell
people in the classes

00:44:29.530 --> 00:44:33.940 align:middle line:84%
is whatever persona
you developed

00:44:33.940 --> 00:44:35.740 align:middle line:84%
to help you survive
your childhood

00:44:35.740 --> 00:44:37.780 align:middle line:84%
and get your emotional
and psychological needs

00:44:37.780 --> 00:44:40.630 align:middle line:84%
met when you were seven
or eight, fantastic.

00:44:40.630 --> 00:44:42.490 align:middle line:84%
Whatever it was, if
you were the cool guy,

00:44:42.490 --> 00:44:44.530 align:middle line:84%
if you were the jock,
if you were the--

00:44:44.530 --> 00:44:45.910 align:middle line:90%
whatever you were, it's great.

00:44:45.910 --> 00:44:49.510 align:middle line:84%
But now that you're 35, I
bet that those same qualities

00:44:49.510 --> 00:44:52.450 align:middle line:84%
are hindering you from getting
the authentic love that you

00:44:52.450 --> 00:44:53.770 align:middle line:90%
really crave.

00:44:53.770 --> 00:44:54.940 align:middle line:90%
So there's an irony there.

00:44:54.940 --> 00:44:57.580 align:middle line:84%
So at some point
in time after you

00:44:57.580 --> 00:45:01.120 align:middle line:84%
realize that you've become
what you love from your parents

00:45:01.120 --> 00:45:05.080 align:middle line:84%
and caregivers and you've become
what you hate, the opposite--

00:45:05.080 --> 00:45:07.240 align:middle line:84%
to individuate-- you
have to pull yourself up

00:45:07.240 --> 00:45:10.340 align:middle line:84%
by your own bootstraps and
say, this is who I want to be.

00:45:10.340 --> 00:45:12.340 align:middle line:84%
And you have to realize
that that's a luxury.

00:45:12.340 --> 00:45:14.257 align:middle line:84%
There's been people who
don't have enough food

00:45:14.257 --> 00:45:16.900 align:middle line:84%
or who are running from tigers
and doing all this crazy stuff,

00:45:16.900 --> 00:45:20.560 align:middle line:84%
and you live in this Western
industrialized country

00:45:20.560 --> 00:45:22.920 align:middle line:84%
where you're like, I
want to fly to the moon.

00:45:22.920 --> 00:45:23.920 align:middle line:90%
I want to make a record.

00:45:23.920 --> 00:45:24.730 align:middle line:90%
I want to paint.

00:45:24.730 --> 00:45:26.230 align:middle line:90%
I want to do these things.

00:45:26.230 --> 00:45:28.370 align:middle line:90%
And that's a privilege.

00:45:28.370 --> 00:45:31.630 align:middle line:84%
And so you have to really
cultivate gratitude, cultivate

00:45:31.630 --> 00:45:34.720 align:middle line:84%
non-reactivity, and
be able to show up

00:45:34.720 --> 00:45:38.770 align:middle line:84%
in the present moment
as love so that you

00:45:38.770 --> 00:45:40.690 align:middle line:90%
attract that from other people.

00:45:40.690 --> 00:45:43.900 align:middle line:84%
You can't just, as I said,
say, James, be vulnerable,

00:45:43.900 --> 00:45:45.450 align:middle line:90%
be loving, you know?

00:45:45.450 --> 00:45:49.030 align:middle line:84%
The best you can do is inspire
them to be their highest self

00:45:49.030 --> 00:45:51.822 align:middle line:90%
by you showing up that way.

00:45:51.822 --> 00:45:52.780 align:middle line:90%
>> That's so beautiful.

00:45:52.780 --> 00:45:54.760 align:middle line:84%
And I really-- I play
with that a little bit.

00:45:54.760 --> 00:45:58.060 align:middle line:84%
I play with the
gratitude process a lot,

00:45:58.060 --> 00:45:59.110 align:middle line:90%
I mean, because--

00:45:59.110 --> 00:46:01.510 align:middle line:84%
one of-- someone I
met a long time ago.

00:46:01.510 --> 00:46:03.310 align:middle line:84%
And I've interviewed,
fortunately,

00:46:03.310 --> 00:46:05.890 align:middle line:84%
hundreds and hundreds of
people who I look up to,

00:46:05.890 --> 00:46:07.330 align:middle line:90%
yourself included.

00:46:07.330 --> 00:46:12.190 align:middle line:84%
And one of them said, turn your
have-to's into a get-to, right?

00:46:12.190 --> 00:46:15.540 align:middle line:84%
Not many people get the
opportunity to start a company

00:46:15.540 --> 00:46:16.660 align:middle line:90%
or do this or that.

00:46:16.660 --> 00:46:18.430 align:middle line:84%
It's like, whoa,
I get to do that.

00:46:18.430 --> 00:46:20.200 align:middle line:90%
You look-- 90%--

00:46:20.200 --> 00:46:23.960 align:middle line:84%
or 88% of the world
is not a WEIRD,

00:46:23.960 --> 00:46:28.510 align:middle line:84%
a Western, industrialized, rich,
educated, democratic country

00:46:28.510 --> 00:46:30.250 align:middle line:90%
of people-- group of people.

00:46:30.250 --> 00:46:32.590 align:middle line:90%
They're just living day to day.

00:46:32.590 --> 00:46:34.780 align:middle line:84%
But then their happiness
is generally higher.

00:46:34.780 --> 00:46:38.740 align:middle line:84%
So their gratefulness
is that they got up,

00:46:38.740 --> 00:46:41.080 align:middle line:84%
that they survived, that
they had a meal, you know?

00:46:41.080 --> 00:46:43.390 align:middle line:84%
Our gratefulness is, like,
well, where's my paycheck?

00:46:43.390 --> 00:46:44.813 align:middle line:84%
Where's my 401(k)
retirement plan?

00:46:44.813 --> 00:46:46.480 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, because we've
been fooled and--

00:46:46.480 --> 00:46:47.563 align:middle line:90%
I'm so sorry to interrupt.

00:46:47.563 --> 00:46:51.310 align:middle line:84%
But we've been fooled into
this system that has told us--

00:46:51.310 --> 00:46:55.690 align:middle line:84%
they've given us these signals
that if you have this big house

00:46:55.690 --> 00:46:56.600 align:middle line:90%
you will be happy.

00:46:56.600 --> 00:46:58.900 align:middle line:84%
If you have this beautiful
wife, you'll be happy.

00:46:58.900 --> 00:47:02.380 align:middle line:84%
If you make two kids and
send them to this school,

00:47:02.380 --> 00:47:03.530 align:middle line:90%
you'll be happy.

00:47:03.530 --> 00:47:07.870 align:middle line:84%
And what I feel is the
midlife crisis in America

00:47:07.870 --> 00:47:13.420 align:middle line:84%
is really this overwhelming
sense of betrayal,

00:47:13.420 --> 00:47:16.390 align:middle line:84%
because I have friends
who did all those things,

00:47:16.390 --> 00:47:17.830 align:middle line:84%
they accomplished
all those goals,

00:47:17.830 --> 00:47:19.750 align:middle line:90%
and they're not happy, right?

00:47:19.750 --> 00:47:23.410 align:middle line:84%
And so then they start to do
the materials, the things.

00:47:23.410 --> 00:47:24.400 align:middle line:90%
They buy a Porsche.

00:47:24.400 --> 00:47:25.540 align:middle line:90%
They get a mistress.

00:47:25.540 --> 00:47:29.230 align:middle line:84%
They go to Vegas or whatever,
and that doesn't work either.

00:47:29.230 --> 00:47:32.720 align:middle line:84%
And then they have to figure
out, like, OK, what am I doing?

00:47:32.720 --> 00:47:34.000 align:middle line:90%
I did everything right.

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:35.690 align:middle line:90%
That didn't make me happy.

00:47:35.690 --> 00:47:39.430 align:middle line:84%
I have to really sit
down and figure this out

00:47:39.430 --> 00:47:40.690 align:middle line:90%
at 40 years old.

00:47:40.690 --> 00:47:42.460 align:middle line:90%
I have to-- you know?

00:47:42.460 --> 00:47:43.660 align:middle line:90%
And it's a really--

00:47:43.660 --> 00:47:47.110 align:middle line:84%
it's a conundrum that we live
in this society with all these

00:47:47.110 --> 00:47:48.490 align:middle line:90%
freedoms and we're--

00:47:48.490 --> 00:47:51.910 align:middle line:84%
America's always, like, 12th
or 19th on the happiness scale.

00:47:51.910 --> 00:47:53.890 align:middle line:84%
And as I mentioned,
all the people who are

00:47:53.890 --> 00:47:57.760 align:middle line:84%
on pharmaceuticals, who take
these medications every morning

00:47:57.760 --> 00:48:00.740 align:middle line:84%
just to get through
their day, and they're--

00:48:00.740 --> 00:48:05.800 align:middle line:84%
we're so-- 3.5 billion
people live on $1.90 a day.

00:48:05.800 --> 00:48:06.860 align:middle line:90%
None of those people--

00:48:06.860 --> 00:48:09.760 align:middle line:84%
I just came from Erewhon
with the $8 coffee,

00:48:09.760 --> 00:48:12.310 align:middle line:90%
and it's like it's Burning Man.

00:48:12.310 --> 00:48:14.292 align:middle line:84%
Everyone's just
so rich in there.

00:48:14.292 --> 00:48:15.250 align:middle line:90%
You look at the prices.

00:48:15.250 --> 00:48:16.120 align:middle line:90%
It's insane.

00:48:16.120 --> 00:48:17.750 align:middle line:84%
And you have to
think to yourself,

00:48:17.750 --> 00:48:20.890 align:middle line:84%
yeah, 25% of these people took
anti-depressants this morning,

00:48:20.890 --> 00:48:21.690 align:middle line:90%
you know?

00:48:21.690 --> 00:48:22.780 align:middle line:90%
What?

00:48:22.780 --> 00:48:24.010 align:middle line:90%
Really?

00:48:24.010 --> 00:48:29.170 align:middle line:84%
And you're-- who sleep in a bed
with nine other people or who

00:48:29.170 --> 00:48:30.460 align:middle line:90%
share meals--

00:48:30.460 --> 00:48:35.170 align:middle line:84%
like, I see kids in their
cars eating on the way.

00:48:35.170 --> 00:48:36.180 align:middle line:90%
They're on the phone.

00:48:36.180 --> 00:48:39.040 align:middle line:84%
They got a latte
and the earbuds.

00:48:39.040 --> 00:48:41.290 align:middle line:84%
And I'm like, you're going
to kill somebody and end up

00:48:41.290 --> 00:48:45.010 align:middle line:84%
in jail because you're
trying to be so productive.

00:48:45.010 --> 00:48:47.970 align:middle line:84%
But happiness is
not in productivity.

00:48:47.970 --> 00:48:50.620 align:middle line:84%
Happiness is, like,
I'm here with you.

00:48:50.620 --> 00:48:52.390 align:middle line:84%
Like, I want to be
with other people.

00:48:52.390 --> 00:48:53.920 align:middle line:90%
We're interdependent.

00:48:53.920 --> 00:48:56.680 align:middle line:84%
We need to really learn
how to break bread.

00:48:56.680 --> 00:49:02.110 align:middle line:84%
And in America,
we've just eradicated

00:49:02.110 --> 00:49:05.740 align:middle line:84%
the basic fundamental
emotional needs,

00:49:05.740 --> 00:49:09.460 align:middle line:84%
and then we diagnose
these people as whatever

00:49:09.460 --> 00:49:10.480 align:middle line:90%
and give them pills.

00:49:10.480 --> 00:49:18.800 align:middle line:84%
So for me, we need an inversion
of our political and economic

00:49:18.800 --> 00:49:19.600 align:middle line:90%
systems.

00:49:19.600 --> 00:49:21.230 align:middle line:84%
And as we were
discussing earlier--

00:49:21.230 --> 00:49:25.060 align:middle line:84%
you know, TS Eliot
wrote in the '40s,

00:49:25.060 --> 00:49:28.270 align:middle line:84%
does it end with a
bang or a whimper?

00:49:28.270 --> 00:49:32.460 align:middle line:84%
And I thought, like, Obama
