00:49:56.650 --> 00:49:59.230 align:middle line:90%
And I don't know.

00:49:59.230 --> 00:50:00.730 align:middle line:84%
I don't know what's
going to happen.

00:50:00.730 --> 00:50:02.147 align:middle line:84%
Is there going to
be a revolution?

00:50:02.147 --> 00:50:05.100 align:middle line:84%
Is China going to say we don't
want to loan you money anymore?

00:50:05.100 --> 00:50:07.060 align:middle line:90%
Like, what's going to happen?

00:50:07.060 --> 00:50:11.200 align:middle line:84%
But people like you
and I, hopefully, we're

00:50:11.200 --> 00:50:13.090 align:middle line:90%
team transition.

00:50:13.090 --> 00:50:16.840 align:middle line:84%
We're here so when all these
buildings, all the light

00:50:16.840 --> 00:50:18.850 align:middle line:84%
goes off and there's
no electricity

00:50:18.850 --> 00:50:21.940 align:middle line:84%
and there's no heat,
we can figure out,

00:50:21.940 --> 00:50:23.800 align:middle line:84%
oh yeah, I read about
this in the book.

00:50:23.800 --> 00:50:26.290 align:middle line:84%
This is how you make a
fire from two sticks.

00:50:26.290 --> 00:50:28.263 align:middle line:84%
I think we can
survive this week,

00:50:28.263 --> 00:50:29.680 align:middle line:84%
because in America
everyone's just

00:50:29.680 --> 00:50:31.820 align:middle line:84%
thinking, like, oh,
I want a Ferrari

00:50:31.820 --> 00:50:34.670 align:middle line:84%
and then I want a Lamborghini
and I want this stuff

00:50:34.670 --> 00:50:37.300 align:middle line:84%
and I want this more stuff
and I want-- no one's happy.

00:50:37.300 --> 00:50:38.320 align:middle line:90%
So I don't know.

00:50:38.320 --> 00:50:42.590 align:middle line:90%
I feel like the Earth is this--

00:50:42.590 --> 00:50:48.010 align:middle line:84%
Gaia is this
mechanism, and humanity

00:50:48.010 --> 00:50:54.130 align:middle line:84%
killing a billion pigs, a
billion cows, and the way

00:50:54.130 --> 00:50:56.830 align:middle line:84%
that they're slaughtered, what
we've done to the oceans--

00:50:56.830 --> 00:51:00.070 align:middle line:84%
like, we could be
hemorrhaged off of our planet

00:51:00.070 --> 00:51:03.250 align:middle line:84%
because we've been
so deleterious.

00:51:03.250 --> 00:51:05.100 align:middle line:90%
We've caused so much harm.

00:51:05.100 --> 00:51:10.730 align:middle line:84%
And it's in our interpersonal
relationships with each other.

00:51:10.730 --> 00:51:13.510 align:middle line:84%
It's not even that
this person is--

00:51:13.510 --> 00:51:15.820 align:middle line:84%
what happened in
Sri Lanka yesterday.

00:51:15.820 --> 00:51:18.730 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's Easter and
seven guys go into churches

00:51:18.730 --> 00:51:21.370 align:middle line:84%
and blow themselves up
and kill 207 people.

00:51:21.370 --> 00:51:28.680 align:middle line:90%
I mean, I have nothing--

00:51:28.680 --> 00:51:31.160 align:middle line:90%
it's just so-- it's--

00:51:31.160 --> 00:51:32.950 align:middle line:90%
I want to say it's embarrassing.

00:51:32.950 --> 00:51:35.800 align:middle line:84%
It's embarrassing that
we're human beings

00:51:35.800 --> 00:51:39.280 align:middle line:84%
and we allow other
human beings to think

00:51:39.280 --> 00:51:42.700 align:middle line:84%
that this is an activity
that they should partake in.

00:51:42.700 --> 00:51:50.070 align:middle line:84%
How did that happen that
we're just so misguided?

00:51:50.070 --> 00:51:52.463 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, it is shocking.

00:51:52.463 --> 00:51:53.880 align:middle line:84%
I don't know that
we can go there.

00:51:53.880 --> 00:51:54.880 align:middle line:90%
That's a big discussion.

00:51:54.880 --> 00:51:57.960 align:middle line:84%
I probably think where
we could transition too--

00:51:57.960 --> 00:51:59.250 align:middle line:90%
what you touched on earlier--

00:51:59.250 --> 00:52:01.740 align:middle line:84%
is talking about this
happiness conundrum

00:52:01.740 --> 00:52:04.810 align:middle line:84%
and how we want all this,
but then we're not happy.

00:52:04.810 --> 00:52:06.990 align:middle line:84%
And you quickly brushed
over a few practical steps

00:52:06.990 --> 00:52:07.800 align:middle line:90%
that we can take.

00:52:07.800 --> 00:52:09.758 align:middle line:84%
So maybe let's focus on
that a little bit more.

00:52:09.758 --> 00:52:13.240 align:middle line:84%
Like, gratitude practice,
what does it look like?

00:52:13.240 --> 00:52:14.190 align:middle line:90%
How do we do that?

00:52:14.190 --> 00:52:16.187 align:middle line:84%
Meditation, what
does it look like?

00:52:16.187 --> 00:52:17.020 align:middle line:90%
How do you teach it?

00:52:17.020 --> 00:52:18.090 align:middle line:90%
What is that like?

00:52:18.090 --> 00:52:20.970 align:middle line:84%
What other practices
are there that, I guess,

00:52:20.970 --> 00:52:25.950 align:middle line:84%
are all-encompassing in terms
of trauma, happiness, whatever?

00:52:25.950 --> 00:52:28.530 align:middle line:84%
They seem to be something
that you just recommend

00:52:28.530 --> 00:52:30.570 align:middle line:90%
as broad strokes for people.

00:52:30.570 --> 00:52:33.420 align:middle line:84%
What-- how do these
practical applications

00:52:33.420 --> 00:52:36.900 align:middle line:84%
of consciousness or
awareness or authenticity

00:52:36.900 --> 00:52:37.960 align:middle line:90%
and how do they work?

00:52:37.960 --> 00:52:40.230 align:middle line:84%
>> So knowing how
the mind operates--

00:52:40.230 --> 00:52:41.340 align:middle line:90%
and I'm very privileged.

00:52:41.340 --> 00:52:44.810 align:middle line:84%
In my office, when
patients walk out,

00:52:44.810 --> 00:52:49.390 align:middle line:84%
there's these big billboards for
Hulu and all these companies.

00:52:49.390 --> 00:52:51.630 align:middle line:84%
But there's also some kind
of home across the street,

00:52:51.630 --> 00:52:56.340 align:middle line:84%
and there's always a kind
of a homeless person that

00:52:56.340 --> 00:52:59.010 align:middle line:84%
had their leg amputated
or some kind of person who

00:52:59.010 --> 00:53:01.770 align:middle line:84%
has to live in an
assisted living facility.

00:53:01.770 --> 00:53:07.210 align:middle line:84%
And it's interesting
because our minds look up.

00:53:07.210 --> 00:53:09.790 align:middle line:84%
But if you want to
compare yourself,

00:53:09.790 --> 00:53:12.820 align:middle line:84%
you could just as easily compare
yourself, particularly me--

00:53:12.820 --> 00:53:15.090 align:middle line:84%
and when I see the
guy across street

00:53:15.090 --> 00:53:17.190 align:middle line:84%
in the wheelchair
with one leg, my mind

00:53:17.190 --> 00:53:18.585 align:middle line:90%
is like, that could be me.

00:53:18.585 --> 00:53:22.230 align:middle line:84%
I don't look up and see some
celebrity in a sports car

00:53:22.230 --> 00:53:25.560 align:middle line:84%
and say, that could be me,
but a lot of people do.

00:53:25.560 --> 00:53:28.650 align:middle line:84%
And that's what media and
social media teaches you.

00:53:28.650 --> 00:53:31.440 align:middle line:90%
It teaches you to--

00:53:31.440 --> 00:53:34.300 align:middle line:84%
if I work hard, I can
be the next whoever.

00:53:34.300 --> 00:53:35.100 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:53:35.100 --> 00:53:36.930 align:middle line:90%
Accept who you are today.

00:53:36.930 --> 00:53:40.050 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, you can try to
make your life better,

00:53:40.050 --> 00:53:44.490 align:middle line:84%
but know the things that are
going to just make you happy,

00:53:44.490 --> 00:53:47.820 align:middle line:84%
and it's going to be the quality
connecting with other people,

00:53:47.820 --> 00:53:49.830 align:middle line:84%
being grateful for
what you do have,

00:53:49.830 --> 00:53:52.650 align:middle line:84%
and then having these tools such
as yoga and meditation so that

00:53:52.650 --> 00:53:58.140 align:middle line:84%
you cultivate being present
and then also non-reactivity,

00:53:58.140 --> 00:54:00.300 align:middle line:90%
because your mind is built to--

00:54:00.300 --> 00:54:04.020 align:middle line:84%
you're basically a
bundle of reactions

00:54:04.020 --> 00:54:08.090 align:middle line:90%
waiting for stimuli, which is--

00:54:08.090 --> 00:54:10.770 align:middle line:84%
you know, if you see one thing,
you're going to be like--

00:54:10.770 --> 00:54:12.550 align:middle line:90%
you'll have this reaction to it.

00:54:12.550 --> 00:54:15.540 align:middle line:84%
So what I'm trying to do
is get people to just tune

00:54:15.540 --> 00:54:17.880 align:middle line:84%
into their breath, be
in the present moment,

00:54:17.880 --> 00:54:22.830 align:middle line:84%
and explore their prejudices and
own them and say, like, yeah,

00:54:22.830 --> 00:54:27.490 align:middle line:84%
this happened to me, I was
traumatized, and I'm safe now.

00:54:27.490 --> 00:54:29.550 align:middle line:84%
So I don't need that
defense mechanism

00:54:29.550 --> 00:54:31.650 align:middle line:90%
of being this other thing.

00:54:31.650 --> 00:54:34.020 align:middle line:84%
So as you know in the book,
I break down authenticity

00:54:34.020 --> 00:54:36.810 align:middle line:84%
into attachment, atonement,
attunement, presence,

00:54:36.810 --> 00:54:37.950 align:middle line:90%
and congruence.

00:54:37.950 --> 00:54:40.620 align:middle line:84%
So attachment is knowing
your attachment dynamic,

00:54:40.620 --> 00:54:43.140 align:middle line:84%
knowing that if you've had
five failed relationships

00:54:43.140 --> 00:54:47.730 align:middle line:84%
and this particular thing
always happens, you're there.

00:54:47.730 --> 00:54:50.040 align:middle line:84%
You're contributing
to that happening.

00:54:50.040 --> 00:54:54.720 align:middle line:84%
That's your-- that's a
ramification of your way

00:54:54.720 --> 00:54:58.290 align:middle line:84%
of believing that the universe
is either abundant and full

00:54:58.290 --> 00:55:02.970 align:middle line:84%
of love and full of grace or
you have to hoard and you have

00:55:02.970 --> 00:55:04.583 align:middle line:84%
to be suspicious
of other people,

00:55:04.583 --> 00:55:06.250 align:middle line:84%
because if you turn
your back, they'll--

00:55:06.250 --> 00:55:07.050 align:middle line:90%
you.

00:55:07.050 --> 00:55:09.890 align:middle line:84%
You know, you have a
basic underlying paradigm,

00:55:09.890 --> 00:55:11.640 align:middle line:84%
so you should know
your attachment dynamic

00:55:11.640 --> 00:55:16.830 align:middle line:84%
because that-- you can then
think of how you are showing up

00:55:16.830 --> 00:55:17.730 align:middle line:90%
in the world.

00:55:17.730 --> 00:55:20.760 align:middle line:84%
And then atonement
is at onement.

00:55:20.760 --> 00:55:22.910 align:middle line:90%
You're basically a child of God.

00:55:22.910 --> 00:55:24.840 align:middle line:84%
You're whole, and
you're perfect.

00:55:24.840 --> 00:55:26.880 align:middle line:84%
And there's room
for improvement,

00:55:26.880 --> 00:55:32.370 align:middle line:84%
meaning that you have this
ego which has been tempered,

00:55:32.370 --> 00:55:38.340 align:middle line:84%
let's say, or colored by your
parents, who your soul chose,

00:55:38.340 --> 00:55:41.670 align:middle line:84%
and then reading the
newspaper and going to schools

00:55:41.670 --> 00:55:43.360 align:middle line:84%
and having all this
pressure on you.

00:55:43.360 --> 00:55:46.080 align:middle line:84%
So for atonement, you
just need to forgive.

00:55:46.080 --> 00:55:50.100 align:middle line:84%
You have to forgive
unequivocally, because those--

00:55:50.100 --> 00:55:55.260 align:middle line:84%
any time you don't forgive,
that is your desire

00:55:55.260 --> 00:55:57.900 align:middle line:90%
to share your suffering.

00:55:57.900 --> 00:56:01.270 align:middle line:90%
As a species, we enjoy--

00:56:01.270 --> 00:56:05.910 align:middle line:90%
and I say that sadly.

00:56:05.910 --> 00:56:09.120 align:middle line:84%
But if you look at
the Middle East,

00:56:09.120 --> 00:56:13.530 align:middle line:84%
let's say, we enjoy paying
our suffering forward.

00:56:13.530 --> 00:56:17.340 align:middle line:84%
There's drones killing people
in Afghanistan on my behalf

00:56:17.340 --> 00:56:19.050 align:middle line:90%
today, right?

00:56:19.050 --> 00:56:21.870 align:middle line:84%
Those people-- I don't
know if they're with ISIS

00:56:21.870 --> 00:56:23.760 align:middle line:90%
or the Taliban or whatever.

00:56:23.760 --> 00:56:26.110 align:middle line:84%
But we pay our
suffering forward.

00:56:26.110 --> 00:56:31.110 align:middle line:84%
It's our mentality as
opposed to figuring out

00:56:31.110 --> 00:56:34.510 align:middle line:84%
what those people want and
what we want and saying,

00:56:34.510 --> 00:56:36.310 align:middle line:84%
how can we make this
a win-win situation.

00:56:36.310 --> 00:56:38.370 align:middle line:90%
We're saying, you killed my son.

00:56:38.370 --> 00:56:42.090 align:middle line:84%
I need to know that
you know how bad you

00:56:42.090 --> 00:56:45.360 align:middle line:84%
made me feel by killing my son,
so I have to kill your son.

00:56:45.360 --> 00:56:46.860 align:middle line:90%
That's the Code of Hammurabi.

00:56:46.860 --> 00:56:48.710 align:middle line:90%
That's our entire legal system.

00:56:48.710 --> 00:56:50.600 align:middle line:84%
And instead, it's
only going to change

00:56:50.600 --> 00:56:53.510 align:middle line:84%
when some brave mother-- and
it happens occasionally--

00:56:53.510 --> 00:56:59.470 align:middle line:84%
in Israel or
Palestine says, no, I

00:56:59.470 --> 00:57:02.340 align:middle line:84%
am not going to pay
my suffering forward.

00:57:02.340 --> 00:57:05.720 align:middle line:90%
I am going to choose love.

00:57:05.720 --> 00:57:08.210 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to choose
skillful solutions.

00:57:08.210 --> 00:57:11.810 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to hug
that woman and not

00:57:11.810 --> 00:57:15.680 align:middle line:84%
make sure that I make
her feel my suffering.

00:57:15.680 --> 00:57:19.460 align:middle line:84%
It's absurd when you think about
it, and yet our world functions

00:57:19.460 --> 00:57:21.380 align:middle line:84%
on this notion of
justice, which means

00:57:21.380 --> 00:57:23.330 align:middle line:90%
I have to kill your family.

00:57:23.330 --> 00:57:24.620 align:middle line:90%
That's insane.

00:57:24.620 --> 00:57:26.423 align:middle line:90%
So forgiveness--

00:57:26.423 --> 00:57:27.590 align:middle line:90%
>> Let's stay on that point.

00:57:27.590 --> 00:57:31.240 align:middle line:84%
How does that work to a father
that abused you or to others?

00:57:31.240 --> 00:57:32.040 align:middle line:90%
The same?

00:57:32.040 --> 00:57:34.520 align:middle line:84%
Do you have to forgive
them as opposed to sort

00:57:34.520 --> 00:57:35.870 align:middle line:84%
of carrying that suffering
forward and doing it--

00:57:35.870 --> 00:57:36.490 align:middle line:90%
>> I know, I know.

00:57:36.490 --> 00:57:36.870 align:middle line:90%
>> No.

00:57:36.870 --> 00:57:37.520 align:middle line:90%
Is that what you're saying?

00:57:37.520 --> 00:57:38.405 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, 100%.

00:57:38.405 --> 00:57:40.280 align:middle line:84%
>> Instead of carrying
that suffering forward

00:57:40.280 --> 00:57:42.827 align:middle line:84%
and psychologically or
subconsciously abusing your own

00:57:42.827 --> 00:57:43.910 align:middle line:90%
child with that language--

00:57:43.910 --> 00:57:44.840 align:middle line:90%
>> Right, exactly.

00:57:44.840 --> 00:57:46.040 align:middle line:84%
>> Can you cover that as
well before your next point?

00:57:46.040 --> 00:57:46.840 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, please.

00:57:46.840 --> 00:57:49.850 align:middle line:90%
So you can't change the past.

00:57:49.850 --> 00:57:54.830 align:middle line:84%
If your parents had
blunt tools, you

00:57:54.830 --> 00:57:58.190 align:middle line:84%
have to say they did the best
they could with the tools

00:57:58.190 --> 00:57:59.480 align:middle line:90%
that they had.

00:57:59.480 --> 00:58:01.040 align:middle line:84%
And you have to
understand, there's

00:58:01.040 --> 00:58:03.830 align:middle line:84%
very few parents
who are sociopaths.

00:58:03.830 --> 00:58:05.930 align:middle line:84%
They just-- they're going
through their stuff.

00:58:05.930 --> 00:58:07.500 align:middle line:90%
They have poor tools.

00:58:07.500 --> 00:58:10.910 align:middle line:84%
And then they take it out on
our kids in some ways, right?

00:58:10.910 --> 00:58:15.410 align:middle line:84%
But for us, our
generation, we just

00:58:15.410 --> 00:58:18.850 align:middle line:84%
have to say they did
the best they could.

00:58:18.850 --> 00:58:20.930 align:middle line:90%
And as I said, they--

00:58:20.930 --> 00:58:23.630 align:middle line:84%
the real healing comes
when they come to us

00:58:23.630 --> 00:58:24.920 align:middle line:90%
at some point in time--

00:58:24.920 --> 00:58:26.450 align:middle line:84%
maybe on their
death bed or-- and

00:58:26.450 --> 00:58:30.290 align:middle line:84%
they say, I could
have loved more.

00:58:30.290 --> 00:58:33.760 align:middle line:84%
That's when the healing
comes, when you have that

00:58:33.760 --> 00:58:36.530 align:middle line:84%
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH] and you
come together and you realize

00:58:36.530 --> 00:58:40.700 align:middle line:84%
that you were part of this thing
and you have a good life now

00:58:40.700 --> 00:58:45.050 align:middle line:84%
and you just have
to accept, really,

00:58:45.050 --> 00:58:48.110 align:middle line:84%
everything that you've
gone through because having

00:58:48.110 --> 00:58:52.010 align:middle line:84%
an adverse relationship with
reality is only hurting you.

00:58:52.010 --> 00:58:55.070 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that's the insanity
of the human condition,

00:58:55.070 --> 00:58:59.720 align:middle line:84%
the consciousness, the mind
trying to change the past.

00:58:59.720 --> 00:59:02.630 align:middle line:84%
Trying to shove that square
peg into a round hole

00:59:02.630 --> 00:59:04.790 align:middle line:90%
causes our own suffering.

00:59:04.790 --> 00:59:08.180 align:middle line:84%
So forgiveness-- and yes,
it's a hard pill to swallow.

00:59:08.180 --> 00:59:11.090 align:middle line:84%
If it's too close to the trauma,
if something terrible happened

00:59:11.090 --> 00:59:15.410 align:middle line:84%
yesterday, it's hard for me
to be like, OK, I'm going to--

00:59:15.410 --> 00:59:16.880 align:middle line:84%
what do I have to
learn from this?

00:59:16.880 --> 00:59:17.990 align:middle line:90%
How did I show up?

00:59:17.990 --> 00:59:19.760 align:middle line:84%
How did I bring
this onto myself?

00:59:19.760 --> 00:59:21.230 align:middle line:90%
Why was I there?

00:59:21.230 --> 00:59:24.350 align:middle line:84%
Why did that car
just come into me?

00:59:24.350 --> 00:59:27.380 align:middle line:84%
And this happened to me
September 4th last year.

00:59:27.380 --> 00:59:28.790 align:middle line:84%
I was just driving
down the road.

00:59:28.790 --> 00:59:32.660 align:middle line:84%
Someone came across five lanes
of traffic, turned towards me,

00:59:32.660 --> 00:59:34.050 align:middle line:90%
hit the gas.

00:59:34.050 --> 00:59:35.190 align:middle line:90%
I had brand new car.

00:59:35.190 --> 00:59:36.560 align:middle line:90%
It's a Honda Civic--

00:59:36.560 --> 00:59:38.240 align:middle line:90%
blew the whole thing up, right?

00:59:38.240 --> 00:59:42.638 align:middle line:84%
I'm sitting there,
and I had to check--

00:59:42.638 --> 00:59:44.180 align:middle line:84%
you know, there's
people coming over,

00:59:44.180 --> 00:59:46.388 align:middle line:84%
and I had to check to see
if my legs were still there

00:59:46.388 --> 00:59:48.390 align:middle line:90%
because I was not in shock.

00:59:48.390 --> 00:59:49.640 align:middle line:90%
I mean, I was conscious.

00:59:49.640 --> 00:59:51.540 align:middle line:90%
But I had the airbag blow up.

00:59:51.540 --> 00:59:54.090 align:middle line:84%
And have you ever had
an airbag blow up?

00:59:54.090 --> 00:59:56.000 align:middle line:84%
It's like being
shot in the chest.

00:59:56.000 --> 00:59:57.020 align:middle line:90%
It's insane.

00:59:57.020 --> 00:59:58.490 align:middle line:90%
And it saved my life.

00:59:58.490 --> 00:59:59.900 align:middle line:90%
I'd be dead right now, right?

00:59:59.900 --> 01:00:03.188 align:middle line:84%
So-- but if you're
a small person

01:00:03.188 --> 01:00:05.480 align:middle line:84%
and an airbag hits you in
the face, you're gone, right?

01:00:05.480 --> 01:00:06.345 align:middle line:90%
So I'm a big person.

01:00:06.345 --> 01:00:07.970 align:middle line:84%
The airbag hits me
in the chest, but it

01:00:07.970 --> 01:00:09.020 align:middle line:90%
knocks the wind out of me.

01:00:09.020 --> 01:00:09.820 align:middle line:90%
I'm bruised.

01:00:09.820 --> 01:00:12.230 align:middle line:84%
I'm all-- there's blood
all over the place, right?

01:00:12.230 --> 01:00:16.130 align:middle line:84%
And so obviously I have
PTSD from the car accident

01:00:16.130 --> 01:00:19.700 align:middle line:84%
33 years ago, and I'm
just doing this body scan,

01:00:19.700 --> 01:00:22.550 align:middle line:84%
and I'm breathing, and
I'm like, OK, am I--

01:00:22.550 --> 01:00:23.840 align:middle line:90%
will I live through this?

01:00:23.840 --> 01:00:27.150 align:middle line:84%
What is damaged-- like, this
whole thing that's going on.

01:00:27.150 --> 01:00:32.240 align:middle line:84%
And at the end of the
day, the other guy--

01:00:32.240 --> 01:00:35.330 align:middle line:84%
I don't know what happened-- had
an epileptic fit or something.

01:00:35.330 --> 01:00:37.250 align:middle line:84%
He didn't wake up in
the morning and say,

01:00:37.250 --> 01:00:39.800 align:middle line:84%
you know what, I'm going
to swerve into traffic

01:00:39.800 --> 01:00:43.860 align:middle line:84%
and try to kill some long-haired
Jew at 3:15 this afternoon.

01:00:43.860 --> 01:00:47.000 align:middle line:84%
Like, he didn't have the
intention of doing that.

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:48.260 align:middle line:90%
So you just have to forgive.

01:00:48.260 --> 01:00:49.250 align:middle line:90%
This was an accident.

01:00:49.250 --> 01:00:51.200 align:middle line:90%
It's a car accident.

01:00:51.200 --> 01:00:53.510 align:middle line:90%
It's car accident.

01:00:53.510 --> 01:00:54.740 align:middle line:90%
That's the language.

01:00:54.740 --> 01:00:55.790 align:middle line:90%
It's an accident.

01:00:55.790 --> 01:00:58.340 align:middle line:84%
There's no intentionality
behind it, right?

01:00:58.340 --> 01:00:59.630 align:middle line:90%
These things happen.

01:00:59.630 --> 01:01:04.460 align:middle line:84%
And whatever can inspire
people to forgive and not pay

01:01:04.460 --> 01:01:08.060 align:middle line:84%
their suffering forward
is what we need to teach.

01:01:08.060 --> 01:01:11.820 align:middle line:90%


01:01:11.820 --> 01:01:12.900 align:middle line:90%
>> The first step was--

01:01:12.900 --> 01:01:13.470 align:middle line:90%
>> Attachment--

01:01:13.470 --> 01:01:14.100 align:middle line:90%
>> Attachment, then atonement.

01:01:14.100 --> 01:01:15.030 align:middle line:90%
>> Atonement.

01:01:15.030 --> 01:01:18.150 align:middle line:84%
Attunement is-- so
I write in the book,

01:01:18.150 --> 01:01:21.990 align:middle line:84%
"mirror neurons don't
fire via text message."

01:01:21.990 --> 01:01:23.790 align:middle line:84%
We delude ourselves
into thinking

01:01:23.790 --> 01:01:26.580 align:middle line:84%
we're connecting with other
people through our devices.

01:01:26.580 --> 01:01:27.690 align:middle line:90%
We need this.

01:01:27.690 --> 01:01:32.760 align:middle line:84%
So Carl Rogers was a
psychologist in the 1950s,

01:01:32.760 --> 01:01:39.090 align:middle line:84%
and he taught that
psychotherapists

01:01:39.090 --> 01:01:42.780 align:middle line:84%
create a safe space
to enable clients

01:01:42.780 --> 01:01:44.910 align:middle line:90%
to re-parent themselves.

01:01:44.910 --> 01:01:46.770 align:middle line:84%
So the other component
that's really

01:01:46.770 --> 01:01:52.410 align:middle line:84%
interesting about parenting
is that if something

01:01:52.410 --> 01:01:55.320 align:middle line:84%
goes wrong in a household,
whether it's a mother

01:01:55.320 --> 01:01:57.690 align:middle line:84%
having a migraine or
the parents fighting

01:01:57.690 --> 01:02:02.220 align:middle line:84%
or things like that, children,
up until a certain age,

01:02:02.220 --> 01:02:06.210 align:middle line:84%
assimilate that is there must be
something wrong with me, right?

01:02:06.210 --> 01:02:10.380 align:middle line:84%
So we have this epidemic in
our culture of low self-esteem,

01:02:10.380 --> 01:02:11.700 align:middle line:90%
low self-worth.

01:02:11.700 --> 01:02:15.960 align:middle line:84%
And for me, its
roots are in the fact

01:02:15.960 --> 01:02:19.860 align:middle line:84%
that we have to figure out
another way of interacting

01:02:19.860 --> 01:02:25.320 align:middle line:84%
with young people so that they
don't assimilate the world's

01:02:25.320 --> 01:02:29.280 align:middle line:84%
trauma as, if I were perfect,
then mommy and daddy wouldn't

01:02:29.280 --> 01:02:33.790 align:middle line:84%
have gotten divorced, because
it's just how our minds work,

01:02:33.790 --> 01:02:34.620 align:middle line:90%
right?

01:02:34.620 --> 01:02:38.070 align:middle line:84%
And then it shows up
later as I'll only

01:02:38.070 --> 01:02:39.540 align:middle line:90%
be happy when I'm president.

01:02:39.540 --> 01:02:41.220 align:middle line:84%
I'll only be happy
when I'm married.

01:02:41.220 --> 01:02:42.762 align:middle line:84%
I'll only be happy
when I'm divorced.

01:02:42.762 --> 01:02:44.860 align:middle line:84%
I'll only be happy--
and this whole thing.

01:02:44.860 --> 01:02:45.660 align:middle line:90%
No.

01:02:45.660 --> 01:02:46.770 align:middle line:90%
This is what you have.

01:02:46.770 --> 01:02:47.970 align:middle line:90%
You have the present moment.

01:02:47.970 --> 01:02:49.240 align:middle line:84%
If you're not happy
now, I could walk out

01:02:49.240 --> 01:02:51.720 align:middle line:84%
into the street in two
minutes and be hit by a car.

01:02:51.720 --> 01:02:53.430 align:middle line:90%
That's my life.

01:02:53.430 --> 01:02:54.910 align:middle line:90%
This is the present moment.

01:02:54.910 --> 01:02:55.710 align:middle line:90%
This is a gift.

01:02:55.710 --> 01:02:56.310 align:middle line:90%
You have this.

01:02:56.310 --> 01:02:57.180 align:middle line:90%
We're here today.

01:02:57.180 --> 01:02:59.800 align:middle line:84%
We have enough
food to eat, and I

01:02:59.800 --> 01:03:01.983 align:middle line:84%
get to hang out
with you guys, and I

01:03:01.983 --> 01:03:03.900 align:middle line:84%
took a-- you went into
the ocean this morning.

01:03:03.900 --> 01:03:04.700 align:middle line:90%
That's amazing.

01:03:04.700 --> 01:03:05.910 align:middle line:90%
I went to a boxing class.

01:03:05.910 --> 01:03:07.200 align:middle line:90%
I'm 53 years old.

01:03:07.200 --> 01:03:09.330 align:middle line:84%
I started taking boxing
lessons last week.

01:03:09.330 --> 01:03:10.440 align:middle line:90%
I'm terrible.

01:03:10.440 --> 01:03:12.310 align:middle line:90%
It's so exciting.

01:03:12.310 --> 01:03:14.630 align:middle line:90%
It's exciting because I--

01:03:14.630 --> 01:03:16.740 align:middle line:84%
to think, like,
OK, move this hip

01:03:16.740 --> 01:03:19.120 align:middle line:84%
and move this and
breathe out and that's

01:03:19.120 --> 01:03:21.300 align:middle line:90%
this and to learn something new.

01:03:21.300 --> 01:03:22.740 align:middle line:90%
I've never boxed before.

01:03:22.740 --> 01:03:24.060 align:middle line:90%
I bought boxing gloves.

01:03:24.060 --> 01:03:24.900 align:middle line:90%
It's exciting.

01:03:24.900 --> 01:03:26.490 align:middle line:90%
I'm terrible.

01:03:26.490 --> 01:03:27.745 align:middle line:90%
I'm the worst.

01:03:27.745 --> 01:03:30.120 align:middle line:84%
There's little people in the
room who could just kill me.

01:03:30.120 --> 01:03:31.810 align:middle line:90%
And to me, that's exciting.

01:03:31.810 --> 01:03:35.590 align:middle line:84%
So I like learning, so I'll
put myself in new situations.

01:03:35.590 --> 01:03:37.590 align:middle line:84%
So attachment,
atonement, attunement,

01:03:37.590 --> 01:03:39.160 align:middle line:90%
connecting with other people--

01:03:39.160 --> 01:03:45.030 align:middle line:84%
just learning how to
reflect their facial

01:03:45.030 --> 01:03:46.510 align:middle line:90%
affect back to them.

01:03:46.510 --> 01:03:48.420 align:middle line:84%
So it's a weird
thing in our culture.

01:03:48.420 --> 01:03:49.940 align:middle line:90%
Some people are taught to smile.

01:03:49.940 --> 01:03:52.440 align:middle line:84%
They walk into the room, and
they're like this or something.

01:03:52.440 --> 01:03:54.450 align:middle line:84%
But we really have
to carve out time--

01:03:54.450 --> 01:03:57.570 align:middle line:84%
and it could be in psychotherapy
or it could be with your wife

01:03:57.570 --> 01:04:00.390 align:middle line:84%
or with your kids or
somebody-- where people just

01:04:00.390 --> 01:04:02.790 align:middle line:84%
validate your
emotional experience,

01:04:02.790 --> 01:04:06.235 align:middle line:84%
because a lot of what goes on
in our society is invalidation.

01:04:06.235 --> 01:04:07.110 align:middle line:90%
It's not intentional.

01:04:07.110 --> 01:04:09.402 align:middle line:84%
But when I go on into Whole
Foods and I'm trying to buy

01:04:09.402 --> 01:04:12.090 align:middle line:84%
something and the kids are
on text message and I'm--

01:04:12.090 --> 01:04:14.392 align:middle line:84%
I'm just sitting
there like, I thought

01:04:14.392 --> 01:04:16.350 align:middle line:84%
that this was going to
be a loving interaction.

01:04:16.350 --> 01:04:18.683 align:middle line:84%
I need to get this ice cream
and go home and eat it now,

01:04:18.683 --> 01:04:20.748 align:middle line:84%
and you're not paying
attention to me.

01:04:20.748 --> 01:04:22.290 align:middle line:84%
And there's these
subconscious things

01:04:22.290 --> 01:04:25.920 align:middle line:84%
that go on that affect us,
whether it's not getting 30

01:04:25.920 --> 01:04:28.440 align:middle line:90%
likes on your Instagram post--

01:04:28.440 --> 01:04:30.810 align:middle line:84%
I just got a buddy onto
Instagram, and he's--

01:04:30.810 --> 01:04:32.610 align:middle line:84%
it's, like, three days,
and he's addicted.

01:04:32.610 --> 01:04:34.720 align:middle line:84%
He's 60 years old, and
it's like this new thing.

01:04:34.720 --> 01:04:35.720 align:middle line:90%
He's like a little baby.

01:04:35.720 --> 01:04:38.010 align:middle line:84%
He's like, oh, I only got
eight likes on that one.

01:04:38.010 --> 01:04:40.110 align:middle line:84%
I said, what are
you doing, you know?

01:04:40.110 --> 01:04:43.230 align:middle line:84%
You're measuring your
life by these things?

01:04:43.230 --> 01:04:51.510 align:middle line:84%
So attuning to other people and
really showing up so that we

01:04:51.510 --> 01:04:52.770 align:middle line:90%
cannot feel crazy--

01:04:52.770 --> 01:04:55.140 align:middle line:84%
because if you just sit
there with your own thoughts

01:04:55.140 --> 01:04:59.070 align:middle line:84%
and don't have the facial
recognition of what we're

01:04:59.070 --> 01:05:01.980 align:middle line:84%
doing now-- like, right,
wow, that's challenging

01:05:01.980 --> 01:05:03.780 align:middle line:84%
or, wow, that's really
exciting, you know?

01:05:03.780 --> 01:05:06.860 align:middle line:84%
That makes you feel comfortable
with your own emotional

01:05:06.860 --> 01:05:07.860 align:middle line:90%
experience of the world.

01:05:07.860 --> 01:05:10.750 align:middle line:84%
So that's why attunement
is so important.

01:05:10.750 --> 01:05:12.030 align:middle line:90%
And then the--

01:05:12.030 --> 01:05:15.030 align:middle line:84%
>> Can we speak on this point
to Marshall Rosenberg's work?

01:05:15.030 --> 01:05:15.240 align:middle line:90%
>> Oh yeah.

01:05:15.240 --> 01:05:16.040 align:middle line:90%
Fantastic.

01:05:16.040 --> 01:05:18.090 align:middle line:84%
>> I love that you brought
it up because to me--

01:05:18.090 --> 01:05:21.450 align:middle line:84%
actually, I found out about
nonviolent communication

01:05:21.450 --> 01:05:25.140 align:middle line:84%
through one of my mentors,
Laurentine's godfather, who

01:05:25.140 --> 01:05:27.507 align:middle line:84%
got it as part of
a reading book club

01:05:27.507 --> 01:05:29.090 align:middle line:84%
as part of a Siddhi
yoga group, right?

01:05:29.090 --> 01:05:29.520 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, yeah.

01:05:29.520 --> 01:05:30.450 align:middle line:90%
>> And so we--

01:05:30.450 --> 01:05:31.350 align:middle line:90%
I got recommended it.

01:05:31.350 --> 01:05:31.860 align:middle line:90%
I read it.

01:05:31.860 --> 01:05:33.485 align:middle line:84%
And it came at a
really important time,

01:05:33.485 --> 01:05:37.020 align:middle line:84%
because in life, you're always
surrounded by people going

01:05:37.020 --> 01:05:41.100 align:middle line:84%
through challenge, whether it's
your parents, employees, team,

01:05:41.100 --> 01:05:42.810 align:middle line:90%
loved ones, whatever.

01:05:42.810 --> 01:05:47.760 align:middle line:84%
And I found that I was being
very unemotionally available

01:05:47.760 --> 01:05:51.540 align:middle line:84%
or not as emotionally available
as I could be in the language

01:05:51.540 --> 01:05:53.940 align:middle line:84%
that I used, in the
way that I listened.

01:05:53.940 --> 01:05:55.510 align:middle line:84%
And this book
changed everything,

01:05:55.510 --> 01:05:58.500 align:middle line:84%
and I think it speaks
to the atonement period

01:05:58.500 --> 01:06:03.120 align:middle line:84%
because it helps you
validate and just let

01:06:03.120 --> 01:06:05.770 align:middle line:84%
them express their emotions,
and that's part of the healing,

01:06:05.770 --> 01:06:06.570 align:middle line:90%
right?

01:06:06.570 --> 01:06:07.487 align:middle line:90%
So how does this work?

01:06:07.487 --> 01:06:15.860 align:middle line:84%
>> And I'll say that as a man
we're basically built to fix

01:06:15.860 --> 01:06:16.970 align:middle line:90%
shit.

01:06:16.970 --> 01:06:19.352 align:middle line:84%
So a woman comes
home and she says,

01:06:19.352 --> 01:06:21.560 align:middle line:84%
oh, this happened and that
happened and this happened

01:06:21.560 --> 01:06:23.840 align:middle line:84%
and then Joan went to the
cooler and then Bob did this

01:06:23.840 --> 01:06:24.640 align:middle line:90%
and whatever.

01:06:24.640 --> 01:06:28.220 align:middle line:84%
And you or I are like, you tell
Joan that-- and you do this.

01:06:28.220 --> 01:06:30.380 align:middle line:84%
And a woman just hears
that as criticism,

01:06:30.380 --> 01:06:33.090 align:middle line:84%
and then you don't
have sex for a month,

01:06:33.090 --> 01:06:35.450 align:middle line:90%
and then nobody's happy.

01:06:35.450 --> 01:06:38.960 align:middle line:84%
And so we really need
to teach attunement.

01:06:38.960 --> 01:06:41.610 align:middle line:84%
And for men-- the
Marshall Rosenberg,

01:06:41.610 --> 01:06:43.430 align:middle line:90%
the nonviolent communications--

01:06:43.430 --> 01:06:46.520 align:middle line:90%
it's removing blame.

01:06:46.520 --> 01:06:50.550 align:middle line:84%
So you're owning your
own emotional experience.

01:06:50.550 --> 01:06:53.030 align:middle line:84%
And if you do that
in a vulnerable way

01:06:53.030 --> 01:06:54.920 align:middle line:84%
like I did when I
wrote that letter

01:06:54.920 --> 01:06:58.910 align:middle line:84%
to the driver of the car, if
you show up authentically,

01:06:58.910 --> 01:07:00.530 align:middle line:90%
you inspire people.

01:07:00.530 --> 01:07:02.960 align:middle line:84%
If I come-- if we go out
for coffee and I'm like,

01:07:02.960 --> 01:07:05.870 align:middle line:84%
James, I really want you to
be authentic with me today,

01:07:05.870 --> 01:07:07.223 align:middle line:90%
you're like, what?

01:07:07.223 --> 01:07:09.140 align:middle line:84%
You're not going to show
up and be like, yeah,

01:07:09.140 --> 01:07:11.150 align:middle line:90%
that's a good idea, right?

01:07:11.150 --> 01:07:14.330 align:middle line:84%
But if I sit here and I'm just
like, oh, man, my cat's sick

01:07:14.330 --> 01:07:18.680 align:middle line:84%
and this is a thing and I
show some kind of, like--

01:07:18.680 --> 01:07:21.840 align:middle line:90%
I'm not, like, this whatever--

01:07:21.840 --> 01:07:24.500 align:middle line:84%
it'll hopefully inspire you
to put a hand on my shoulder,

01:07:24.500 --> 01:07:27.710 align:middle line:84%
show up and just attune to
my emotional experience,

01:07:27.710 --> 01:07:29.510 align:middle line:90%
and then that validates it.

01:07:29.510 --> 01:07:33.500 align:middle line:84%
So the Marshall
Rosenberg I teach as--

01:07:33.500 --> 01:07:36.620 align:middle line:84%
we had in this country,
40 years ago, Mad Libs.

01:07:36.620 --> 01:07:38.090 align:middle line:84%
Did you ever have
that, Mad Libs?

01:07:38.090 --> 01:07:40.580 align:middle line:84%
It's like this--
you put in words.

01:07:40.580 --> 01:07:42.715 align:middle line:84%
There's a blank spot,
and there's sentences,

01:07:42.715 --> 01:07:44.090 align:middle line:84%
but there's blank
spots, and then

01:07:44.090 --> 01:07:46.670 align:middle line:84%
you put in adjectives
or nouns or things.

01:07:46.670 --> 01:07:50.450 align:middle line:84%
But it's basically "I
feel--" and the blank spot

01:07:50.450 --> 01:07:51.920 align:middle line:90%
is a feeling state--

01:07:51.920 --> 01:07:54.350 align:middle line:84%
"when--" and then
the next part--

01:07:54.350 --> 01:07:56.240 align:middle line:84%
the next blank spot
is an observation.

01:07:56.240 --> 01:08:01.310 align:middle line:84%
"I feel frustrated when
there are dishes in the sink

01:08:01.310 --> 01:08:06.050 align:middle line:84%
because I need--" and
then you put in a need--

01:08:06.050 --> 01:08:08.390 align:middle line:90%
"I need order in my life.

01:08:08.390 --> 01:08:10.850 align:middle line:84%
In the future--" and then you
put a request in-- "could you

01:08:10.850 --> 01:08:13.610 align:middle line:84%
please not have the
dishes in the sink?'

01:08:13.610 --> 01:08:17.609 align:middle line:84%
And instead of showing up
at home one night and just

01:08:17.609 --> 01:08:20.040 align:middle line:90%
going, dishes in the sink, man--

01:08:20.040 --> 01:08:20.840 align:middle line:90%
right?

01:08:20.840 --> 01:08:22.040 align:middle line:84%
And then the other
person's going

01:08:22.040 --> 01:08:23.520 align:middle line:84%
to be like, well, if
you don't like them,

01:08:23.520 --> 01:08:24.410 align:middle line:90%
then you should do them, right?

01:08:24.410 --> 01:08:25.460 align:middle line:90%
And it's a fight.

01:08:25.460 --> 01:08:27.260 align:middle line:84%
So you need to have
this language where

01:08:27.260 --> 01:08:29.779 align:middle line:84%
you enroll people in
having a conversation so

01:08:29.779 --> 01:08:31.609 align:middle line:90%
that it's a win-win situation.

01:08:31.609 --> 01:08:33.200 align:middle line:84%
People can show
up and they don't

01:08:33.200 --> 01:08:35.790 align:middle line:84%
have to be the bundle
of defense mechanisms.

01:08:35.790 --> 01:08:39.950 align:middle line:84%
They could say, OK, you're
showing up in a loving manner.

01:08:39.950 --> 01:08:41.540 align:middle line:84%
I want to show up
in a loving manner.

01:08:41.540 --> 01:08:43.550 align:middle line:84%
And let's make this
a win-win situation.

01:08:43.550 --> 01:08:47.569 align:middle line:84%
So I-- all those tools, the
reflective listening, Harville

01:08:47.569 --> 01:08:50.300 align:middle line:84%
Hendrix, Imago,
nonviolent communications,

01:08:50.300 --> 01:08:52.670 align:middle line:84%
Marshall Rosenberg,
and some of the things

01:08:52.670 --> 01:08:55.460 align:middle line:84%
from John Gottman's book
on the "Seven Principles

01:08:55.460 --> 01:08:57.410 align:middle line:84%
of a Highly
Successful Marriage,"

01:08:57.410 --> 01:08:58.819 align:middle line:84%
all that stuff--
any time you can

01:08:58.819 --> 01:09:01.790 align:middle line:84%
change your way of
phrasing something--

01:09:01.790 --> 01:09:03.830 align:middle line:84%
and I'll give you
my favorite one.

01:09:03.830 --> 01:09:06.500 align:middle line:90%
And this one is--

01:09:06.500 --> 01:09:09.470 align:middle line:84%
this one goes to the
forgiveness aspect also.

01:09:09.470 --> 01:09:11.899 align:middle line:84%
But someone taught me
years ago-- they said,

01:09:11.899 --> 01:09:15.680 align:middle line:84%
OK, try this phrase
out with this person

01:09:15.680 --> 01:09:17.779 align:middle line:90%
you're having a fight with.

01:09:17.779 --> 01:09:20.600 align:middle line:84%
Please forgive me
for not understanding

01:09:20.600 --> 01:09:22.819 align:middle line:84%
the way you choose to
show your love for me.

01:09:22.819 --> 01:09:25.620 align:middle line:90%


01:09:25.620 --> 01:09:28.720 align:middle line:84%
And then you shut
up indefinitely.

01:09:28.720 --> 01:09:33.479 align:middle line:84%
And it's basically-- it's
called a pattern interrupt,

01:09:33.479 --> 01:09:35.700 align:middle line:84%
because the person
expects you to blame them.

01:09:35.700 --> 01:09:37.920 align:middle line:84%
But if you say to
them, I know you

01:09:37.920 --> 01:09:41.850 align:middle line:84%
love me and you want
what's best for me,

01:09:41.850 --> 01:09:46.350 align:middle line:84%
but that really hurt my
feelings, that phrase--

01:09:46.350 --> 01:09:51.090 align:middle line:84%
particularly if you're having
some kind of contention,

01:09:51.090 --> 01:09:52.620 align:middle line:90%
something acrimonious--

01:09:52.620 --> 01:09:54.870 align:middle line:84%
if you can say,
please forgive me

01:09:54.870 --> 01:09:56.667 align:middle line:84%
for not understanding
the way you're

01:09:56.667 --> 01:09:58.500 align:middle line:84%
choosing to show your
love for me right now.

01:09:58.500 --> 01:10:02.460 align:middle line:90%


01:10:02.460 --> 01:10:05.820 align:middle line:90%
Again, we need to find--

01:10:05.820 --> 01:10:09.740 align:middle line:84%
we need to elevate our
discourse so that we inspire

01:10:09.740 --> 01:10:12.182 align:middle line:84%
the other person to show
up in a loving manner

01:10:12.182 --> 01:10:13.640 align:middle line:84%
because that's what
we really want.

01:10:13.640 --> 01:10:16.010 align:middle line:84%
But, instead, we
do this crazy thing

01:10:16.010 --> 01:10:19.490 align:middle line:84%
in our society, which
I call-- it's yes but.

01:10:19.490 --> 01:10:22.160 align:middle line:84%
So in my family
where I grew up, I

01:10:22.160 --> 01:10:25.885 align:middle line:84%
would say, look, the
sky's blue, and then

01:10:25.885 --> 01:10:28.520 align:middle line:84%
my grandma would be, yeah, but
it's going to rain tomorrow.

01:10:28.520 --> 01:10:32.810 align:middle line:84%
So-- I know, but that's--
because we're taught to try

01:10:32.810 --> 01:10:34.880 align:middle line:90%
to arrive at the truth.

01:10:34.880 --> 01:10:39.680 align:middle line:84%
But what we inadvertently do
with these phrases like "yes

01:10:39.680 --> 01:10:43.490 align:middle line:84%
but" is we invalidate the other
person's emotional experience.

01:10:43.490 --> 01:10:47.120 align:middle line:84%
So I had this one
person at Esalen,

01:10:47.120 --> 01:10:51.230 align:middle line:84%
and she had a
younger sister who--

01:10:51.230 --> 01:10:52.580 align:middle line:90%
it's such a beautiful story--

01:10:52.580 --> 01:10:57.560 align:middle line:84%
who hadn't found her way
yet and was kind of just

01:10:57.560 --> 01:10:59.200 align:middle line:90%
flopping about the house.

01:10:59.200 --> 01:11:05.090 align:middle line:84%
And I could tell already
that the way the older sister

01:11:05.090 --> 01:11:08.210 align:middle line:84%
was showing her love for her
was like, you should get a job.

01:11:08.210 --> 01:11:09.372 align:middle line:90%
You should go to school.

01:11:09.372 --> 01:11:10.580 align:middle line:90%
You should do this, whatever.

01:11:10.580 --> 01:11:12.310 align:middle line:84%
And the girl was just
thinking, I'm a piece of shit,

01:11:12.310 --> 01:11:14.893 align:middle line:84%
I'm a piece of shit, I'm a piece
of shit, I'm a piece of shit.

01:11:14.893 --> 01:11:16.640 align:middle line:90%
So I told her to say--

01:11:16.640 --> 01:11:21.590 align:middle line:84%
I told her, for the next
week, don't say "yes

01:11:21.590 --> 01:11:24.320 align:middle line:84%
but" whenever your younger
sister says anything.

01:11:24.320 --> 01:11:26.830 align:middle line:90%
Just change it to "yes and."

01:11:26.830 --> 01:11:29.420 align:middle line:84%
And I got to call
a week later, and--

01:11:29.420 --> 01:11:31.970 align:middle line:90%


01:11:31.970 --> 01:11:35.550 align:middle line:84%
that's the smallest thing,
just taking one word, "but,"

01:11:35.550 --> 01:11:38.630 align:middle line:84%
and changing it to "and,"
and it just totally

01:11:38.630 --> 01:11:41.180 align:middle line:90%
transformed the relationship.

01:11:41.180 --> 01:11:42.230 align:middle line:90%
>> Amazing.

01:11:42.230 --> 01:11:43.270 align:middle line:90%
Marshall's fantastic.

01:11:43.270 --> 01:11:44.070 align:middle line:90%
I love it.

01:11:44.070 --> 01:11:44.660 align:middle line:90%
And what does he say?

01:11:44.660 --> 01:11:46.090 align:middle line:84%
He says, don't put
a butt-- don't throw

01:11:46.090 --> 01:11:46.970 align:middle line:90%
a butt in front of a jackal.

01:11:46.970 --> 01:11:48.830 align:middle line:84%
You know how he does little
animals and everything?

01:11:48.830 --> 01:11:49.910 align:middle line:90%
>> I know, it's fantastic.

01:11:49.910 --> 01:11:51.368 align:middle line:84%
>> And I find I'm
doing it as well.

01:11:51.368 --> 01:11:53.720 align:middle line:84%
Like, I've got a
new 13-year-old son.

01:11:53.720 --> 01:11:55.860 align:middle line:84%
And he'll be like,
oh, look at that,

01:11:55.860 --> 01:11:58.280 align:middle line:84%
and I'm trying to prove
my intelligence to him.

01:11:58.280 --> 01:12:00.040 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, but this and
that and this and that.

01:12:00.040 --> 01:12:02.630 align:middle line:84%
I'm like, whoa, whoa,
whoa, whoa, huh?

01:12:02.630 --> 01:12:03.950 align:middle line:90%
It's a wake-up call, but it's--

01:12:03.950 --> 01:12:07.580 align:middle line:90%
I love being triggered--

01:12:07.580 --> 01:12:09.170 align:middle line:84%
now I love being
triggered because I

01:12:09.170 --> 01:12:11.660 align:middle line:84%
get to see my own stupidity
and, in that process,

01:12:11.660 --> 01:12:12.702 align:middle line:90%
grow from that awareness.

01:12:12.702 --> 01:12:14.327 align:middle line:84%
>> I'm going to tell
you a funny story.

01:12:14.327 --> 01:12:15.420 align:middle line:90%
This is so embarrassing.

01:12:15.420 --> 01:12:17.660 align:middle line:84%
I was on a date with someone who
I really wanted to go on a date

01:12:17.660 --> 01:12:18.460 align:middle line:90%
with.

01:12:18.460 --> 01:12:20.240 align:middle line:90%
I had met her 30 years ago.

01:12:20.240 --> 01:12:25.860 align:middle line:84%
And her father's one
of my all-time heroes,

01:12:25.860 --> 01:12:28.790 align:middle line:84%
and it just-- it was
very exciting or whatnot.

01:12:28.790 --> 01:12:30.230 align:middle line:90%
And we sit down to dinner.

01:12:30.230 --> 01:12:32.930 align:middle line:84%
And for some-- because I
had to puff up my chest

01:12:32.930 --> 01:12:35.640 align:middle line:84%
because I am proud of the book,
you know, and all those things.

01:12:35.640 --> 01:12:36.440 align:middle line:90%
So I was just--

01:12:36.440 --> 01:12:39.130 align:middle line:84%
I nonchalantly-- she
knew I wrote the book,

01:12:39.130 --> 01:12:40.850 align:middle line:90%
but I nonchalantly mentioned it.

01:12:40.850 --> 01:12:45.020 align:middle line:84%
And she goes, did
you self-publish it?

01:12:45.020 --> 01:12:51.610 align:middle line:84%
And the date went tits
up, and it was awful.

01:12:51.610 --> 01:12:53.140 align:middle line:90%
And for the next hour--

01:12:53.140 --> 01:12:55.450 align:middle line:84%
I didn't realize this
till after the fact,

01:12:55.450 --> 01:12:59.020 align:middle line:84%
but I was trying
to justify my own--

01:12:59.020 --> 01:13:00.510 align:middle line:84%
because I took it
as such a slight,

01:13:00.510 --> 01:13:01.830 align:middle line:84%
and she probably didn't
mean it like that.

01:13:01.830 --> 01:13:03.670 align:middle line:84%
She didn't wake up in
the morning and say,

01:13:03.670 --> 01:13:04.630 align:middle line:84%
you know what I'm
going to do tonight?

01:13:04.630 --> 01:13:05.547 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to mess up--

01:13:05.547 --> 01:13:08.260 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to throw a monkey
wrench into Ira Israel's engine

01:13:08.260 --> 01:13:09.460 align:middle line:90%
by asking this question.

01:13:09.460 --> 01:13:11.200 align:middle line:84%
If she had said,
who's the publisher,

01:13:11.200 --> 01:13:13.300 align:middle line:84%
it wouldn't have affected
me like that at all.

01:13:13.300 --> 01:13:16.248 align:middle line:84%
But it put me on my hind
legs, and I was like--

01:13:16.248 --> 01:13:18.040 align:middle line:84%
because she could make
a phone call and get

01:13:18.040 --> 01:13:20.890 align:middle line:84%
a book published in a second
because of her family.

01:13:20.890 --> 01:13:24.680 align:middle line:84%
But for me, it basically took
15 years to get a publisher,

01:13:24.680 --> 01:13:25.480 align:middle line:90%
you know?

01:13:25.480 --> 01:13:27.400 align:middle line:84%
So it was just
like this-- it was

01:13:27.400 --> 01:13:30.160 align:middle line:84%
this hierarchical, subconscious
thing that happened.

01:13:30.160 --> 01:13:31.237 align:middle line:90%
I'm so embarrassed.

01:13:31.237 --> 01:13:33.070 align:middle line:84%
And I wanted to just
call her and say, like,

01:13:33.070 --> 01:13:35.260 align:middle line:90%
can I have another shot?

01:13:35.260 --> 01:13:38.650 align:middle line:84%
I was just put into
my pain body by you

01:13:38.650 --> 01:13:40.370 align:middle line:90%
asking this innocuous question.

01:13:40.370 --> 01:13:42.580 align:middle line:84%
I don't think you
meant to slight me.

01:13:42.580 --> 01:13:43.600 align:middle line:90%
A lot of famous people--

01:13:43.600 --> 01:13:45.400 align:middle line:84%
Stephen King
self-published his books.

01:13:45.400 --> 01:13:49.060 align:middle line:84%
But for me, I'm so proud that
I actually had a publisher

01:13:49.060 --> 01:13:52.090 align:middle line:84%
and it's Eckhart Tolle's
publisher and I'm-- whatever.

01:13:52.090 --> 01:13:54.370 align:middle line:84%
But the way the
question was phrased--

01:13:54.370 --> 01:13:55.420 align:middle line:90%
and it's so interesting.

01:13:55.420 --> 01:13:57.040 align:middle line:90%
You know, no one's immune.

01:13:57.040 --> 01:14:00.070 align:middle line:84%
You just have to really sit
there and tune in to the person

01:14:00.070 --> 01:14:02.998 align:middle line:84%
and think about, what
are they really saying?

01:14:02.998 --> 01:14:04.540 align:middle line:84%
And then when we're
speaking, we have

01:14:04.540 --> 01:14:09.190 align:middle line:84%
to be very conscious of
the way we phrase things.

01:14:09.190 --> 01:14:11.530 align:middle line:84%
So then the last
part-- attachment,

01:14:11.530 --> 01:14:14.530 align:middle line:84%
atonement, attunement,
presence, and congruence.

01:14:14.530 --> 01:14:15.970 align:middle line:90%
So presence is really simple--

01:14:15.970 --> 01:14:17.860 align:middle line:90%
yoga, meditation.

01:14:17.860 --> 01:14:20.170 align:middle line:84%
Depression relates to
thoughts about the past.

01:14:20.170 --> 01:14:22.670 align:middle line:84%
Anxiety relates to
thoughts about the future.

01:14:22.670 --> 01:14:23.710 align:middle line:90%
The past doesn't exist.

01:14:23.710 --> 01:14:24.790 align:middle line:90%
It's dead and gone.

01:14:24.790 --> 01:14:26.330 align:middle line:90%
The future doesn't exist.

01:14:26.330 --> 01:14:28.100 align:middle line:90%
It's just your expectations.

01:14:28.100 --> 01:14:32.620 align:middle line:84%
So how do depression
and anxiety exist?

01:14:32.620 --> 01:14:38.290 align:middle line:84%
So being in the present moment
and not allowing the prejudices

01:14:38.290 --> 01:14:42.340 align:middle line:84%
from the past to influence your
decisions or your expectations

01:14:42.340 --> 01:14:44.970 align:middle line:84%
or fears about the
future to influence

01:14:44.970 --> 01:14:49.210 align:middle line:84%
is essential to authentic,
loving relationships.

01:14:49.210 --> 01:14:50.830 align:middle line:84%
And then the last
part is congruence.

01:14:50.830 --> 01:14:51.705 align:middle line:90%
>> How do we do that?

01:14:51.705 --> 01:14:52.810 align:middle line:90%
How do we meditate?

01:14:52.810 --> 01:14:54.310 align:middle line:84%
To be present in
a relationship is

01:14:54.310 --> 01:14:57.760 align:middle line:84%
to listen well, to not solve
women's problems, which

01:14:57.760 --> 01:14:58.660 align:middle line:90%
I'm horrible at.

01:14:58.660 --> 01:15:01.550 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I get the list of
problems, and I'm solving them.

01:15:01.550 --> 01:15:02.410 align:middle line:84%
All right, we're going
to book this flight.

01:15:02.410 --> 01:15:02.980 align:middle line:90%
We're going to do this.

01:15:02.980 --> 01:15:03.590 align:middle line:90%
We're going to do that.

01:15:03.590 --> 01:15:04.370 align:middle line:90%
We're going to meet this person.

01:15:04.370 --> 01:15:06.940 align:middle line:84%
We're going to do-- it's
just like, no, just listen.

01:15:06.940 --> 01:15:08.290 align:middle line:90%
Understand the emotion.

01:15:08.290 --> 01:15:09.700 align:middle line:90%
It's profound, and it solves it.

01:15:09.700 --> 01:15:10.720 align:middle line:84%
You're like, whoa,
that's amazing.

01:15:10.720 --> 01:15:12.030 align:middle line:90%
How did that problem go away?

01:15:12.030 --> 01:15:14.600 align:middle line:84%
It screws with a guy's brain,
right, because he-- yeah.

01:15:14.600 --> 01:15:15.080 align:middle line:90%
>> That's great.

01:15:15.080 --> 01:15:15.850 align:middle line:90%
>> A guy is so practical.

01:15:15.850 --> 01:15:17.892 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I first started
getting insight into this

01:15:17.892 --> 01:15:20.078 align:middle line:84%
through David Deida, his
work, and he was just like,

01:15:20.078 --> 01:15:21.870 align:middle line:84%
they want to hug and
they want to be heard.

01:15:21.870 --> 01:15:23.290 align:middle line:84%
And then-- and the
nonviolent communication

01:15:23.290 --> 01:15:24.670 align:middle line:84%
was sort of the
book end of it where

01:15:24.670 --> 01:15:26.253 align:middle line:84%
it was like, OK,
that makes sense now,

01:15:26.253 --> 01:15:29.050 align:middle line:84%
and it gives you tools
to listen better.

01:15:29.050 --> 01:15:31.900 align:middle line:84%
Being present-- OK, so you
can do that through listening,

01:15:31.900 --> 01:15:34.090 align:middle line:84%
like you've spoken,
atonement, being

01:15:34.090 --> 01:15:35.590 align:middle line:90%
attuned to the other person.

01:15:35.590 --> 01:15:37.930 align:middle line:84%
But you're speaking
about meditation now.

01:15:37.930 --> 01:15:40.990 align:middle line:84%
What practice of
meditation do you use?

01:15:40.990 --> 01:15:42.310 align:middle line:90%
Is it mantra based?

01:15:42.310 --> 01:15:43.600 align:middle line:90%
Is it sitting in stillness?

01:15:43.600 --> 01:15:45.790 align:middle line:84%
Is it guided
visualization or whatever?

01:15:45.790 --> 01:15:47.650 align:middle line:90%
What do you prescribe?

01:15:47.650 --> 01:15:51.700 align:middle line:84%
What do you think
works best for people?

01:15:51.700 --> 01:15:54.650 align:middle line:84%
>> There are seven point some
odd billion people on planet

01:15:54.650 --> 01:15:55.450 align:middle line:90%
Earth.

01:15:55.450 --> 01:15:57.970 align:middle line:84%
There are seven points some
odd billion different types

01:15:57.970 --> 01:15:58.990 align:middle line:90%
of meditation.

01:15:58.990 --> 01:16:04.820 align:middle line:84%
For me, mantra
meditation gets me high.

01:16:04.820 --> 01:16:10.540 align:middle line:84%
That's-- and I go to various
gurus, and I'll sit with them.

01:16:10.540 --> 01:16:12.700 align:middle line:90%
And I don't advocate--

01:16:12.700 --> 01:16:17.110 align:middle line:84%
I don't think that the archetype
of guru is functional anymore.

01:16:17.110 --> 01:16:18.940 align:middle line:90%
But there are certain people--

01:16:18.940 --> 01:16:21.400 align:middle line:84%
I sit in their
presence-- that's what

01:16:21.400 --> 01:16:24.540 align:middle line:84%
the word "Upanishad" means,
and I love the Upanishad.

01:16:24.540 --> 01:16:26.050 align:middle line:84%
It's just sitting
in the presence.

01:16:26.050 --> 01:16:27.400 align:middle line:90%
And I feel happy.

01:16:27.400 --> 01:16:29.140 align:middle line:84%
When I sit with the
Dalai Lama and I

01:16:29.140 --> 01:16:34.810 align:middle line:84%
know what he bears and to
see his joy and the way

01:16:34.810 --> 01:16:40.330 align:middle line:84%
he's turned that around and
his love, I'm so inspired.

01:16:40.330 --> 01:16:41.950 align:middle line:90%
Like I-- you know, that--

01:16:41.950 --> 01:16:44.230 align:middle line:90%
so I always seek out--

01:16:44.230 --> 01:16:50.530 align:middle line:84%
whether I go to MOCA and look
at Rothkos or go to the symphony

01:16:50.530 --> 01:16:53.860 align:middle line:84%
and watch Gustavo
Dudamel conduct "Mahler."

01:16:53.860 --> 01:16:56.350 align:middle line:84%
All these people, all these
artists, all these writers

01:16:56.350 --> 01:16:58.690 align:middle line:84%
are seeking the same
thing in some ways, right?

01:16:58.690 --> 01:17:01.312 align:middle line:90%
So for me, I constantly--

01:17:01.312 --> 01:17:04.480 align:middle line:90%


01:17:04.480 --> 01:17:08.110 align:middle line:84%
I'm hungry for how
other people found

01:17:08.110 --> 01:17:11.950 align:middle line:84%
meaning in their
lives, constructed

01:17:11.950 --> 01:17:14.900 align:middle line:84%
loving relationships
and things like that.

01:17:14.900 --> 01:17:19.240 align:middle line:84%
So for me, I practice
mantra meditation.

01:17:19.240 --> 01:17:24.580 align:middle line:84%
But I teach
visualizations because I

01:17:24.580 --> 01:17:28.000 align:middle line:84%
want people to disidentify
with their thoughts.

01:17:28.000 --> 01:17:30.850 align:middle line:90%
So I'll give a visualization.

01:17:30.850 --> 01:17:34.270 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the most common is
the Buddhist one where you're

01:17:34.270 --> 01:17:36.490 align:middle line:90%
sitting at the edge of a river.

01:17:36.490 --> 01:17:40.030 align:middle line:84%
There's a tree off to
the side and a leaf falls

01:17:40.030 --> 01:17:41.860 align:middle line:90%
and whatever thoughts you have--

01:17:41.860 --> 01:17:43.810 align:middle line:84%
oh, I hope I didn't
get a parking ticket.

01:17:43.810 --> 01:17:45.735 align:middle line:90%
You put it on the leaf.

01:17:45.735 --> 01:17:47.860 align:middle line:84%
And you have something
called a mind screen, right?

01:17:47.860 --> 01:17:50.350 align:middle line:84%
And you watch the leaf
go down the stream.

01:17:50.350 --> 01:17:53.980 align:middle line:84%
And when the leaf exits your
mind screen, what you'll notice

01:17:53.980 --> 01:17:56.217 align:middle line:84%
is another thought
comes into my head.

01:17:56.217 --> 01:17:58.300 align:middle line:84%
What am I going to have
for dinner tonight, right?

01:17:58.300 --> 01:18:00.140 align:middle line:90%
And then you put it on.

01:18:00.140 --> 01:18:03.010 align:middle line:84%
So at the end of
that meditation,

01:18:03.010 --> 01:18:07.030 align:middle line:84%
I'll say, point to
the part of your body

01:18:07.030 --> 01:18:09.730 align:middle line:90%
that was watching your thoughts.

01:18:09.730 --> 01:18:14.230 align:middle line:84%
And some people point here, but
in Tibet, mind or heart-- mind

01:18:14.230 --> 01:18:15.310 align:middle line:90%
is here, right?

01:18:15.310 --> 01:18:20.800 align:middle line:90%
So all of our beliefs--

01:18:20.800 --> 01:18:23.560 align:middle line:84%
as I started this conversation
with Thomas Kuhn--

01:18:23.560 --> 01:18:25.600 align:middle line:90%
can be deconstructed.

01:18:25.600 --> 01:18:28.360 align:middle line:84%
But the fact of the matter
is that Descartes put us

01:18:28.360 --> 01:18:32.620 align:middle line:84%
on the wrong thread or path
when he said, "I think,

01:18:32.620 --> 01:18:34.510 align:middle line:90%
therefore I am."

01:18:34.510 --> 01:18:37.330 align:middle line:90%
We're addicted to thinking.

01:18:37.330 --> 01:18:41.000 align:middle line:84%
And our thoughts
are causing us--

01:18:41.000 --> 01:18:42.997 align:middle line:84%
they're encapsulating
the problems.

01:18:42.997 --> 01:18:45.080 align:middle line:84%
And then they're saying,
no, that's not a problem.

01:18:45.080 --> 01:18:46.455 align:middle line:84%
You suffer from
bipolar disorder.

01:18:46.455 --> 01:18:47.830 align:middle line:90%
That's the problem.

01:18:47.830 --> 01:18:48.730 align:middle line:90%
No.

01:18:48.730 --> 01:18:56.980 align:middle line:84%
You're responsible for your
own cognition in some ways.

01:18:56.980 --> 01:19:02.080 align:middle line:84%
If you're unhappy, think
better thoughts, right?

01:19:02.080 --> 01:19:04.570 align:middle line:84%
And that's what-- but that's
what the gratitude list is.

01:19:04.570 --> 01:19:10.540 align:middle line:84%
So being present, for me, means
cultivating non-reactivity.

01:19:10.540 --> 01:19:14.043 align:middle line:84%
You're sitting there,
and you're thinking--

01:19:14.043 --> 01:19:15.460 align:middle line:84%
you're not actually
thinking this,

01:19:15.460 --> 01:19:16.990 align:middle line:84%
but you're like, oh, you
know what happened today?

01:19:16.990 --> 01:19:17.790 align:middle line:90%
I woke up.

01:19:17.790 --> 01:19:21.730 align:middle line:84%
There was $125 charge on a
Shell station on my credit card,

01:19:21.730 --> 01:19:24.310 align:middle line:84%
and I knew that I didn't go
to that Shell station, right?

01:19:24.310 --> 01:19:27.190 align:middle line:84%
So I had to go through
this whole thing,

01:19:27.190 --> 01:19:30.250 align:middle line:84%
and my card was
obviously stolen.

01:19:30.250 --> 01:19:32.200 align:middle line:84%
There's all these tricks
that people do now.

01:19:32.200 --> 01:19:35.098 align:middle line:84%
But it was really interesting
to see the way I was like, OK--

01:19:35.098 --> 01:19:37.390 align:middle line:84%
I was just like, OK, this is
going to suck about a half

01:19:37.390 --> 01:19:38.230 align:middle line:90%
an hour of my life.

01:19:38.230 --> 01:19:39.917 align:middle line:84%
I just have to
figure out how to--

01:19:39.917 --> 01:19:42.500 align:middle line:84%
what's the most efficacious way
of canceling this credit card?

01:19:42.500 --> 01:19:43.910 align:middle line:90%
But yeah, you just--

01:19:43.910 --> 01:19:44.710 align:middle line:90%
that's it.

01:19:44.710 --> 01:19:47.570 align:middle line:84%
You just-- you accept that
these things happen, and you--

01:19:47.570 --> 01:19:48.370 align:middle line:90%
that's it.

01:19:48.370 --> 01:19:49.840 align:middle line:90%
It's over, you know?

01:19:49.840 --> 01:19:52.450 align:middle line:84%
So when you sit there
in the morning--

01:19:52.450 --> 01:19:53.740 align:middle line:90%
and I like to sit there.

01:19:53.740 --> 01:20:07.980 align:middle line:84%
What that does is it lets you
taste the nectar of the divine.

01:20:07.980 --> 01:20:12.770 align:middle line:84%
So yoga and meditation
were devised

01:20:12.770 --> 01:20:17.300 align:middle line:84%
to help you go to the other
side of your thoughts.

01:20:17.300 --> 01:20:20.390 align:middle line:84%
Deepak Chopra calls it
falling into the gap,

01:20:20.390 --> 01:20:22.970 align:middle line:90%
the gap between words.

01:20:22.970 --> 01:20:24.980 align:middle line:84%
Again, we're
addicted to language.

01:20:24.980 --> 01:20:26.690 align:middle line:90%
We're addicted to thinking.

01:20:26.690 --> 01:20:30.870 align:middle line:90%
And we have to be able to--

01:20:30.870 --> 01:20:32.655 align:middle line:84%
my favorite quote
from Marshall McLuhan

01:20:32.655 --> 01:20:34.280 align:middle line:84%
is, "I don't know
who discovered water,

01:20:34.280 --> 01:20:36.750 align:middle line:90%
but I doubt it was a fish."

01:20:36.750 --> 01:20:41.900 align:middle line:84%
So we're swimming in this
language and these emotions

01:20:41.900 --> 01:20:46.970 align:middle line:84%
and capitalism and our way
of being in the world and all

01:20:46.970 --> 01:20:49.370 align:middle line:84%
these things, and
they're contributing

01:20:49.370 --> 01:20:54.470 align:middle line:84%
to our stress and our
anxiety and as us showing up

01:20:54.470 --> 01:20:58.100 align:middle line:84%
like assholes and being
revengeful and starting

01:20:58.100 --> 01:21:00.930 align:middle line:90%
wars and these things.

01:21:00.930 --> 01:21:07.688 align:middle line:84%
And we have to be able
to sit there and just

01:21:07.688 --> 01:21:16.050 align:middle line:84%
tap in to what's underneath
all that craziness.

01:21:16.050 --> 01:21:18.450 align:middle line:84%
And for me, I sit
in the morning,

01:21:18.450 --> 01:21:22.103 align:middle line:84%
and then when my credit
card gets stolen or someone

01:21:22.103 --> 01:21:23.520 align:middle line:84%
cuts me off on the
road or someone

01:21:23.520 --> 01:21:25.680 align:middle line:84%
gives me the wrong
change, I don't

01:21:25.680 --> 01:21:32.670 align:middle line:84%
have to be insane and show up
in some way that's only going

01:21:32.670 --> 01:21:34.320 align:middle line:90%
to exacerbate the situation.

01:21:34.320 --> 01:21:36.330 align:middle line:84%
I can say, oh yeah, my
credit card got stolen.

01:21:36.330 --> 01:21:37.260 align:middle line:90%
It happened for.

01:21:37.260 --> 01:21:38.490 align:middle line:90%
It's going to happen again.

01:21:38.490 --> 01:21:41.430 align:middle line:84%
I have to spend half an hour on
the phone with Chase cancelling

01:21:41.430 --> 01:21:43.080 align:middle line:90%
the credit card.

01:21:43.080 --> 01:21:45.260 align:middle line:84%
Not going to ruin
my life, you know?

01:21:45.260 --> 01:21:46.380 align:middle line:90%
And I did it.

01:21:46.380 --> 01:21:49.830 align:middle line:84%
But we're very
reactive, and so we

01:21:49.830 --> 01:21:52.470 align:middle line:84%
have to cultivate
non-reactivity,

01:21:52.470 --> 01:21:55.273 align:middle line:84%
which is an art form, so
that we're not triggered

01:21:55.273 --> 01:21:56.940 align:middle line:84%
and that we learn
what our triggers are.

01:21:56.940 --> 01:21:58.920 align:middle line:84%
So observing our
thoughts, you sit there.

01:21:58.920 --> 01:22:01.110 align:middle line:84%
And Dan Harris has
that beautiful quote.

01:22:01.110 --> 01:22:03.720 align:middle line:84%
He says, "Meditation's
like being kidnapped

01:22:03.720 --> 01:22:06.360 align:middle line:84%
by the most boring
person on Earth,"

01:22:06.360 --> 01:22:09.150 align:middle line:84%
because if you sit there for
a half an hour in the morning,

01:22:09.150 --> 01:22:13.400 align:middle line:84%
you realize that your mind
has a default mechanism.

01:22:13.400 --> 01:22:14.970 align:middle line:90%
Mine's planning.

01:22:14.970 --> 01:22:17.880 align:middle line:84%
And Sharon Salzberg
says, "My mind

01:22:17.880 --> 01:22:21.900 align:middle line:84%
plans because it
makes me feel safe."

01:22:21.900 --> 01:22:23.320 align:middle line:90%
And maybe it's a Jewish thing.

01:22:23.320 --> 01:22:24.120 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

01:22:24.120 --> 01:22:27.060 align:middle line:84%
But planning-- like,
OK, I have this list

01:22:27.060 --> 01:22:28.860 align:middle line:84%
and I'm going to do
this at 8 o'clock

01:22:28.860 --> 01:22:30.420 align:middle line:84%
and this happens
tomorrow morning.

01:22:30.420 --> 01:22:33.810 align:middle line:84%
And I'm making my
universe orderly.

01:22:33.810 --> 01:22:35.190 align:middle line:90%
So I think--

01:22:35.190 --> 01:22:37.680 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I'm not going to
give myself my own diagnosis.

01:22:37.680 --> 01:22:42.480 align:middle line:84%
But I think I plan because
there was a part of my life

01:22:42.480 --> 01:22:44.400 align:middle line:90%
where I was not in control.

01:22:44.400 --> 01:22:45.420 align:middle line:90%
And my mindset--

01:22:45.420 --> 01:22:47.280 align:middle line:84%
I'm never going to
let that happen again.

01:22:47.280 --> 01:22:49.230 align:middle line:90%
So my mind plans.

01:22:49.230 --> 01:22:52.710 align:middle line:84%
Interestingly-- so now when I
have people come into my office

01:22:52.710 --> 01:22:55.063 align:middle line:84%
and they have OCD,
I'll sit them down

01:22:55.063 --> 01:22:56.730 align:middle line:84%
and I'll do a little
meditation and I'll

01:22:56.730 --> 01:23:02.610 align:middle line:84%
say, OK, this behavior that
you're now calling whatever

01:23:02.610 --> 01:23:05.500 align:middle line:84%
you're calling, at
some point in time,

01:23:05.500 --> 01:23:09.780 align:middle line:84%
it was a solution to a problem
for your seven-year-old mind

01:23:09.780 --> 01:23:12.060 align:middle line:84%
or your nine-year-old
or your 10-year-old mind

01:23:12.060 --> 01:23:16.590 align:middle line:84%
thought, oh, if I just binge
and purge, then x will happen.

01:23:16.590 --> 01:23:18.000 align:middle line:90%
I solved the problem.

01:23:18.000 --> 01:23:18.900 align:middle line:90%
Now you're 35.

01:23:18.900 --> 01:23:20.120 align:middle line:90%
You're bingeing and purging.

01:23:20.120 --> 01:23:21.430 align:middle line:90%
You're unhealthy.

01:23:21.430 --> 01:23:25.770 align:middle line:84%
Let's look at what your mind
was trying to solve then.

01:23:25.770 --> 01:23:27.720 align:middle line:84%
For me, the narrative
that I've constructed

01:23:27.720 --> 01:23:29.970 align:middle line:84%
is, when I was in
traction, it was

01:23:29.970 --> 01:23:31.440 align:middle line:84%
kind of humiliating
to have to have

01:23:31.440 --> 01:23:33.960 align:middle line:84%
somebody do the bedpan
and all these things.

01:23:33.960 --> 01:23:37.540 align:middle line:84%
And my mind said, I'm going to
never let that happen again,

01:23:37.540 --> 01:23:40.682 align:middle line:84%
so I'll create order in my life
by making lists and planning

01:23:40.682 --> 01:23:41.640 align:middle line:90%
and doing these things.

01:23:41.640 --> 01:23:44.640 align:middle line:84%
And then when I'm sitting there
meditating and I catch myself--

01:23:44.640 --> 01:23:46.560 align:middle line:90%
and it's insane.

01:23:46.560 --> 01:23:48.223 align:middle line:84%
You just realize
that this is, like--

01:23:48.223 --> 01:23:50.640 align:middle line:84%
the world's going to show up
the way it's going to show up

01:23:50.640 --> 01:23:54.240 align:middle line:90%
no matter what I plan, right?

01:23:54.240 --> 01:23:55.950 align:middle line:90%
But my mind makes--

01:23:55.950 --> 01:24:00.040 align:middle line:84%
it feels this sense of ease by
having these-- like, OK, well,

01:24:00.040 --> 01:24:02.370 align:middle line:84%
if this happens, that'll
happen, and then I'll do this

01:24:02.370 --> 01:24:03.390 align:middle line:90%
and then I'll say this.

01:24:03.390 --> 01:24:05.820 align:middle line:84%
And I'll have these
fictitious conversations.

01:24:05.820 --> 01:24:08.260 align:middle line:84%
And then I look at myself
having these conversations that

01:24:08.260 --> 01:24:09.510 align:middle line:90%
are never going to take place.

01:24:09.510 --> 01:24:10.370 align:middle line:90%
And I'm like, this is insane.

01:24:10.370 --> 01:24:11.662 align:middle line:90%
Why don't you just go meditate?

01:24:11.662 --> 01:24:13.500 align:middle line:84%
It's going to be a
lot more pleasing.

01:24:13.500 --> 01:24:15.480 align:middle line:84%
And then I get back
to the meditation.

01:24:15.480 --> 01:24:18.810 align:middle line:84%
And so, for me, we're
cultivating non-reactivity

01:24:18.810 --> 01:24:20.880 align:middle line:84%
because we have this
default mechanism,

01:24:20.880 --> 01:24:22.440 align:middle line:90%
this way of being in the world.

01:24:22.440 --> 01:24:23.860 align:middle line:84%
We're always
preparing for things

01:24:23.860 --> 01:24:25.930 align:middle line:84%
and we're trying to
do things and whatnot.

01:24:25.930 --> 01:24:31.560 align:middle line:84%
And we just have
to be able to be

01:24:31.560 --> 01:24:33.690 align:middle line:84%
in the present
moment as our highest

01:24:33.690 --> 01:24:39.420 align:middle line:84%
self without the influences
from our society and all

01:24:39.420 --> 01:24:44.100 align:middle line:84%
these crazy desires that
we think will make us happy

01:24:44.100 --> 01:24:44.920 align:middle line:90%
if we attain--

01:24:44.920 --> 01:24:45.720 align:middle line:90%
and just.

01:24:45.720 --> 01:24:49.770 align:middle line:90%


01:24:49.770 --> 01:24:51.030 align:middle line:90%
>> Beautiful.

01:24:51.030 --> 01:24:52.030 align:middle line:90%
Was that the last one?

01:24:52.030 --> 01:24:53.820 align:middle line:84%
>> No, the last
one is congruence,

01:24:53.820 --> 01:24:56.370 align:middle line:84%
and it starts with this
beautiful quote by André Gide,

01:24:56.370 --> 01:25:00.300 align:middle line:84%
who said, "It is better to be
hated for what you are than

01:25:00.300 --> 01:25:03.300 align:middle line:84%
to be loved for
what you are not."

01:25:03.300 --> 01:25:07.080 align:middle line:84%
So for me, again,
congruence is a privilege

01:25:07.080 --> 01:25:10.440 align:middle line:84%
to live in such a
WEIRD wealthy society

01:25:10.440 --> 01:25:14.730 align:middle line:84%
where you and I get to say, I
want to be a psychotherapist,

01:25:14.730 --> 01:25:17.370 align:middle line:84%
and I go to school, and I
become a psychotherapist,

01:25:17.370 --> 01:25:21.450 align:middle line:84%
and I am able to earn my
living helping other people,

01:25:21.450 --> 01:25:22.990 align:middle line:90%
or I want to be a writer.

01:25:22.990 --> 01:25:27.150 align:middle line:84%
And then you create your
life around your vocation.

01:25:27.150 --> 01:25:30.870 align:middle line:84%
So "voco" in Latin
means calling, right?

01:25:30.870 --> 01:25:34.330 align:middle line:84%
So the universe is giving
us information all the time.

01:25:34.330 --> 01:25:36.900 align:middle line:84%
And we just have to
sit down and meditate

01:25:36.900 --> 01:25:39.010 align:middle line:90%
and say, what does this mean?

01:25:39.010 --> 01:25:44.070 align:middle line:84%
And then you use your best
inferences to say, oh,

01:25:44.070 --> 01:25:46.770 align:middle line:84%
I shouldn't be working
flipping pizzas.

01:25:46.770 --> 01:25:50.010 align:middle line:90%
I love this.

01:25:50.010 --> 01:25:53.340 align:middle line:84%
And then you create your
life so that you can do that.

01:25:53.340 --> 01:25:55.980 align:middle line:84%
And that's what I hope
that my classes and my book

01:25:55.980 --> 01:25:57.900 align:middle line:84%
and the DVDs and
everything inspire people

01:25:57.900 --> 01:26:02.730 align:middle line:84%
to do, because anything
that you do for money,

01:26:02.730 --> 01:26:04.530 align:middle line:90%
you're a prostitute, right?

01:26:04.530 --> 01:26:06.490 align:middle line:84%
And in our country,
all my friends,

01:26:06.490 --> 01:26:07.740 align:middle line:90%
they have golden handcuffs.

01:26:07.740 --> 01:26:09.070 align:middle line:90%
I'm 53 years old.

01:26:09.070 --> 01:26:12.270 align:middle line:84%
If you started working in
1988 when you were my age,

01:26:12.270 --> 01:26:14.670 align:middle line:84%
you make millions
of dollars a year.

01:26:14.670 --> 01:26:19.050 align:middle line:84%
And there's a lot of my friends
who feel, oh, well, my kid--

01:26:19.050 --> 01:26:21.750 align:middle line:84%
this costs this much, and
the mortgage costs this much.

01:26:21.750 --> 01:26:22.650 align:middle line:90%
They hate their jobs.

01:26:22.650 --> 01:26:23.490 align:middle line:90%
They hate their lives.

01:26:23.490 --> 01:26:24.323 align:middle line:90%
And they're trapped.

01:26:24.323 --> 01:26:26.610 align:middle line:84%
That's what a golden
handcuff is, right?

01:26:26.610 --> 01:26:28.830 align:middle line:84%
So at some point
in time, you have

01:26:28.830 --> 01:26:31.440 align:middle line:84%
to sit down and say, what's
going to make me happy,

01:26:31.440 --> 01:26:35.070 align:middle line:84%
and figure it out and find
your vocation, your calling.

01:26:35.070 --> 01:26:38.520 align:middle line:84%
What is the universe telling
you that you should be doing?

01:26:38.520 --> 01:26:41.790 align:middle line:90%
And it's not making money.

01:26:41.790 --> 01:26:44.650 align:middle line:84%
It's not exerting
power over people.

01:26:44.650 --> 01:26:45.720 align:middle line:90%
It's being of service.

01:26:45.720 --> 01:26:50.130 align:middle line:84%
It's being your nature,
which is Buddha nature, which

01:26:50.130 --> 01:26:51.750 align:middle line:90%
is pure love, you know?

01:26:51.750 --> 01:26:52.980 align:middle line:90%
Show up that way.

01:26:52.980 --> 01:26:54.990 align:middle line:90%
Inspire other people to do that.

01:26:54.990 --> 01:26:58.380 align:middle line:84%
And let's make the
world a better place.

01:26:58.380 --> 01:26:59.760 align:middle line:90%
>> Amazing.

01:26:59.760 --> 01:27:01.530 align:middle line:84%
What would be your
sort of message

01:27:01.530 --> 01:27:03.600 align:middle line:84%
for the people
listening to this,

01:27:03.600 --> 01:27:05.450 align:middle line:90%
watching this, hearing from you?

01:27:05.450 --> 01:27:08.560 align:middle line:84%
You know, you've got a very
unique range of studies.

01:27:08.560 --> 01:27:13.050 align:middle line:84%
But if there is some
sort of final message

01:27:13.050 --> 01:27:15.740 align:middle line:84%
you want to leave for people,
I'd love to hear that now.

01:27:15.740 --> 01:27:22.330 align:middle line:90%


01:27:22.330 --> 01:27:24.910 align:middle line:84%
>> Abraham Maslow has
this incredible quote.

01:27:24.910 --> 01:27:28.670 align:middle line:84%
He says, "When the only
tool you have is a hammer,

01:27:28.670 --> 01:27:31.240 align:middle line:90%
every problem resembles a nail."

01:27:31.240 --> 01:27:36.970 align:middle line:84%
So I've been very
privileged post car accident

01:27:36.970 --> 01:27:40.930 align:middle line:84%
to travel around the
world and go to ashrams

01:27:40.930 --> 01:27:43.540 align:middle line:84%
and sit with really,
really smart people,

01:27:43.540 --> 01:27:48.490 align:middle line:84%
and I've aggregated
a set of tools.

01:27:48.490 --> 01:27:50.920 align:middle line:84%
And I know the ones
that work for me,

01:27:50.920 --> 01:27:54.460 align:middle line:90%
and I don't proselytize.

01:27:54.460 --> 01:27:56.920 align:middle line:90%
What I do is I share tools.

01:27:56.920 --> 01:27:58.692 align:middle line:84%
And I say, why
don't you try this?

01:27:58.692 --> 01:27:59.650 align:middle line:90%
Why don't you try that?

01:27:59.650 --> 01:28:00.460 align:middle line:90%
Why don't you try surfing?

01:28:00.460 --> 01:28:01.670 align:middle line:90%
I've never surfed in my life.

01:28:01.670 --> 01:28:04.510 align:middle line:84%
I'll send people to
surfing lessons, you know?

01:28:04.510 --> 01:28:08.950 align:middle line:84%
But I know the things
that resonate with me

01:28:08.950 --> 01:28:13.090 align:middle line:84%
and make me happy, and
I love sharing them

01:28:13.090 --> 01:28:14.690 align:middle line:90%
with the people I love.

01:28:14.690 --> 01:28:17.560 align:middle line:84%
But when students
or patients come in,

01:28:17.560 --> 01:28:20.440 align:middle line:84%
